e Boer as "quite spontaneous. We've had quite a few Japanese students and they vary a lot. Some of them are really shy. They don't know much English and they don't participate and stay in their room a lot of the time. "Riyo wasn't like that. Her English was good. She went to Mount Doug here and she did well, better than some other students we had." He said Mori's grandmother made a prediction years ago that she would be Miss Japan before she was 20, and being named Miss Universe will make Mori's dream of opening a dance school a reality. "I don't have much doubt that she'll achieve what she wants to," de Boer said. Mount Douglas counsellor Cheryl Chapple was thrilled to see Mori named Miss Universe because of her inner beauty. "I think more than anything, it wasn't looks that jumped out but it was her sweetness. She's just a lovely, sweet, very hard-working girl." Mori won the Miss Universe on Monday. Prizes include a diamond and pearl crown valued at $250,000. Â© The Vancouver Sun 2007 John Mayer acts out a bizarre ... Privacy czar warns web users to be wary Students cruising online networking... Deaths may be linked to diabetes drug Health Canada says the deaths ... Fox Sports World Canada Copyright & Permission Rules &copy; 2007 CanWest Interactive, a division of CanWest MediaWorks Publications Inc. . All rights reserved. Unauthorized distribution, transmission or republication strictly prohibited.
