http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/8-0&fd=R&url=http://www.usatoday.com/life/television/news/2007-05-30-debra-messing_N.htm&cid=1116730139&ei=jv1eRsO-FY-oqgO5vv3PDQ Messing's starting over in 'Starter Wife' - USATODAY.com How do I find it? Sign up to receive our free Books e-newsletter and get the top news of the day in your inbox. Breaking news E-mail alerts Get breaking news in your inbox as it happens Messing's starting over in 'Starter Wife' By Donna Freydkin, USA TODAY NEW YORK &#151; Last spring, Debra Messing endured a searing breakup, one that flattened her for two full days. "I was devastated. I was numb and confused," the actress says over tea at the Mercer Hotel in Manhattan. "It was just such an emotionally overwhelming thing." 'Starter Wife' is well-made fluff Debra Messing answers your questions See a clip from 'Starter Wife' She's talking about her last day playing ditzy, droll interior decorator Grace Adler on NBC's groundbreaking hit , which ended its eight-season run last May. But Messing could just as easily be referring to her latest character, plucky divorc&#233;e Molly in the six-hour telefilm , premiering tonight (USA, 9 ET/PT). Like Messing, Molly grapples with momentous changes. Messing went from being one of NBC's Emmy-winning shining stars to unemployed actress. Molly learns, via a phone call, that her Hollywood-studio-head husband is dumping her. "Change is scary. You see that in , and I experienced it with . It's interesting to me that Molly doesn't crawl into bed," Messing says. "I didn't get out of bed for two days. I slept. I didn't do anything." And although Messing, 38, is happily married to screenwriter Daniel Zelman and is the mother of son Roman, 3, she can relate to Molly's turmoil. "Molly and I were going through an incredibly similar experience," Messing says. " was an eight-year marriage, and it ended. I didn't know what I should do next, what I could do next or what I wanted to do next. For eight years, I wasn't allowed to ask those questions." Don't expect Grace Adler's madcap energy and zany sensibility from the actress, who in person is crisp, businesslike and focused. She's well-read, and to maximize her time, she devours books, such as Orhan Pamuk's , "that have a seal on the cover that either says Nobel Prize or the Booker Prize," she says. About the only goofiness on display comes courtesy of her cellphone ringtones: the themes from The Price Is Right "I've spent my life trying to be cool and realizing that I've been a 95-year-old nerd since I was 12," she says, cracking one of just a few smiles. Now that she's not sharing a spacious pad with Will Truman on the Upper West Side, Messing calls herself "a dancing monkey. I'm an actress for hire. I'm not a writer. I'm just waiting for the person to say, 'Debra, you're the person to do this.' " Despite recent supporting turns in feature films (Curtis Hanson's ), she's not angling to go back to work right away. "I have a very full personal life that fulfills me in a way that nothing else can," Messing says. "Having flexibility right now is something I'm enjoying. For eight years, I had a very structured life. Now, I can go wherever I want, whenever I want." On a typical day, she wakes up with her son, puts him down for a nap, takes him to the park, makes dinner and gives him a bath. "We get into pajamas and snuggle and watch ," she says. "The only thing I would add to my day to make it better is more hours, so I could spend an hour reading by myself and an extra hour to sleep. And some more dates with my husband." To report corrections and clarifications, contact Reader Editor By Todd Plitt, USA TODAY Taking it easy: Debra Messing is using her newly flexible schedule to spend more time with her husband and son. USA TODAY welcomes your thoughts, stories and information related to this article. Please stay on topic and be respectful of others. Keep the conversation appropriate for interested readers across the map. Newspaper Home Delivery - Subscribe Today Privacy Policy/Your California Privacy Right Add USATODAY.com RSS feeds
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/16i-0&fd=R&url=http://fredericksburg.com/News/FLS/2007/052007/05312007/288174&cid=1116836906&ei=jv1eRsO-FY-oqgO5vv3PDQ Fredericksburg.com - 'PIRATES' MOVIE NEARLY SINKS Thu, May. 31, 2007 It! Magazine & MyLine Wedding & event planning WWUZ, 96.9, classic rock Photos of the Day Your photos: View and submit Photos of the week Wedding & event planning New Listings in Last 2 days Open Houses This Week Classifieds - Real Estate for Sale Classifieds - Real Estate for Rent The Free Lance&ndash;Star Classifieds 'PIRATES' MOVIE NEARLY SINKS Johnny Depp (left) and Geoffrey Rush star in 'Pirates of the Caribbean: At World's End.' Ashley Judd (left) and Harry Connick Jr. star in 'Bug.' PIRATES OF THE CARIBBEAN: AT WORLD'S END (PG-13) HH STARRING: JOHNNY DEPP, KEIRA KNIGHTLY, ORLANDO BLOOM, GEOFFREY RUSH, CHOW YUN-FAT RUNNING TIME: 168 MIN. The biggest threat to the three main characters here doesn't come from cannon fire, sharp swords or even drowning in sea battles. No, what almost does in the charm and appeal of the third in the Captain Jack Sparrow films is its very bloat. The film suffers from a cobbled-together plot that has so much going on that it very nearly sinks under its own weight. With nearly three hours of action, romance, subplots and just plain silliness to work through, moviegoers will find themselves wiggling in their seats with too many story lines they don't care about. Thanks goodness that every time the tale gets slow and overdone, Depp's visage pops up onscreen. As Sparrow, one of the most memorable characters on the screen in recent years, he saves the action every time he appears. Yes, sometimes he seems as though he's joking with his portrayal, making Sparrow a silly sort of pirate. But he almost winks as he does it, letting you in on the fact that he's having a ball playing this rascally pirate. So you can't help but join him in the merriment. The same holds true to a somewhat smaller extent for Knightly and Bloom as the swashbuckling Elizabeth and the adventurous Will. The first film worked so well because it never strayed far from at least one of the trio. This time out, things get all caught up with Davy Jones, Capt. Barbossa, James Norrington, Bootstrap Bill Turner, Lord Beckett and the ubiquitous Calypso, to the point where the story loses steam from so much sidetracking. The problem begins at the movie's opening, when a group of common folk, including a young boy, is hanged for supposedly supporting or being pirates. What does this add to anything? Nothing, but it is a warning of things to come throughout. Ditto for a long, goofy venture into a version of Davy Jones' Locker that looks an awful lot like a deserted island. When rocks turn into crabs and carry a grounded Black Pearl to a nearby beach, we wonder what Sparrow's been smoking. Battle scenes don't go on as long as in the second film, but there's a whole segment with Yun-Fat's character that doesn't add a thing. Those looking for an amazing moment when Rolling Stone Keith Richards takes the screen as Sparrow's pirate dad will be disappointed as well. Sure, it's cool seeing the rock world collide with a major motion picture, but Richards is as leaden as the gold that all these pirates yearn for. HOW WE RATE 'EM H Don't waste your time. sorry if you miss it. Read more stories about Breaking News - click here to have the latest delivered to your email box or cell phone What do you think? Enter your FredTalk username and password to post a comment on this story. If you are registered on FredTalk or another part of this site, use that login here. Otherwise, you can just Please keep it brief: (512-character limit) By checking this box, you agree to the terms of the 2 drunk charges in a busy night (Thursday, 01:31, The Free Lance-Star) Trucker killed in crash on I-95 (Thursday, 01:19, The Free Lance-Star) APVA says list isn't a negative (Thursday, 00:57, The Free Lance-Star) Doctors, hospital join forces to open 