http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/7i-0&fd=R&url=http://www.dailyherald.com/suburbanliving/story.asp%3Fid%3D318368&cid=1116623090&ei=jv1eRsO-FY-oqgO5vv3PDQ Daily Herald | Suburban Living Subscribe to the Daily Herald Lake in the Hills Thursday, May 31, 2007 7 DAY STORY SEARCH An adult comedy funnier than you can possible conceive Posted Saturday, February 28, 1987 Posted Saturday, February 28, 1987 Posted Thursday, May 31, 2007 If Woody Allen is the comedy king of intellectual morality, then Judd Apatow, after just two features, should be the comedy king of humanistic crassness. "Knocked Up" seals the title for Apatow, the delightfully twisted director/writer of the daffy hit comedy "The 40-Year-Old Virgin" and creator of the short-lived television series "Freaks and Geeks." About that title, "Knocked Up." What a perfectly saucy, sassy and outrageous title for a hilariously irreverent look at romance and sex. This adult comedy earns every aspect of its R rating for its sexy scenes, adult language, raunchy jokes and humorous drug use. Paradoxically, "Knocked Up" qualifies as one of the sweetest, most optimistic views of modern romance I've seen in recent years. Allison Scott (Katherine Hegl), left, waits anxiously with her sister Debbie (Leslie Mann) for the results of a pregnancy test in the Judd Apatow comedy "Knocked Up" I say this despite some abrupt, graphic close-ups of Katherine Heigl's most private region (or at least her stunt double's most private region) as she gives birth to a baby conceived during a night of booze and stupidity. As he did in "Virgin," Apatow spins a story of unexpectedly empathetic characters caught up in juvenile jokes and bathroom humor. Yet, he makes villains of no one and virtual heroes out of all. Every character in "Knocked Up" starts out as an instantly identifiable movie type. But as the story unfolds, Apatow's characters prove themselves to be more than we originally assume. Not just the main characters, either. Nope. All of them, even the small ones such as the rude, obnoxious pediatrician who rediscovers his bedside manner after a verbal pistol-whipping. Or a club bouncer who stands around like a movie prop until he summarizes his job requirements in a knee-slapping monologue way too honest for his miffed female patrons. Or Ben Stone (Seth Rogen), who appears to be a brainless but lovable frat-boy cliché until he knocks up Alison Scott (Heigl) after a boozy one-night stand during which he misconstrues her wishes and forgoes the use of a condom. A few weeks later, Alison realizes somebody made a mistake. She becomes pregnant at the same time she receives her anxiously awaited promotion to be a news announcer on E! How did this promising young woman on the cusp of a dream job get knocked up by a doofus whose maturity level locked in somewhere around his freshman year? Alison's very married sister Debbie (Leslie Mann, alias the real Mrs. Apatow and a featured player in "The 40-Year-Old Virgin") seems more interested in herself than in helping Alison. In a regular movie, Mann's harpy housewife would have remained an easy villain. Apatow gives Debbie a character arc that brings her vulnerability to the surface and renders her all too human. The same thing happens to Paul Rudd, another "Virgin" veteran. He hangs in the background as Debbie's deferring husband Pete, until he gets a chance to show what he's made of. "Knocked Up," like "Virgin" and other Apatow projects, has a knack for addressing life's natural messes with bemused curiosity. It delves into ferociously anti-PC territory, running headlong into issues of maturity, drugs and responsibility, all while armed with a rapier sense of humor and a great affection for its characters. Especially for Heigl, the star of TV's successful dramatic series "Grey's Anatomy." The actress is a magnet for our empathy, and she constructs a character with such credibility that we accept it when Alison decides to try a relationship with Ben, a father-in-law's certifiable worst nightmare. As Ben, Rogen projects a chilling slacker attitude with something hidden beneath the surface. Something good. In a world where lives get buffeted by the twists of uncaring fate, Rogen's Ben is a well-meaning young man whose heart exceeds his IQ. In the Apatow universe, what matters more than that?  Want to write your own review of this movie? Go to www.dailyherald.com/timeout. "Knocked Up"4 stars out of fourOpens today Starring AsKatherine Heigl Alison ScottSeth Rogen Ben StonePaul Rudd PeteLeslie Mann DebbieHarold Ramis Ben's DadWritten and directed by Judd Apatow. Produced by Judd Apatow, Shauna Robertson and Clayton Townsend. A Universal Pictures release. Rated R (sexual situations, drug use, language). Running time: 129 minutes. Email story to a friend Return to Suburban Living front Customer Service Comcast is Hiring Customer Account Executiv... PRODUCTION Auomated cell owner Automation / Machine Operator... Dispatch We're the Company of Choice At EchoStar's DISH Netw... auto *Quick Lube Techs* Dependable, honest & hard working. A... BARTENDER-part time for private country club. Must have exp.... View All Top Jobs A hole in the heart As seen on TV: Do they work? , Paddock Publications, Inc. |
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/13-6&fd=R&url=http://metromix.chicagotribune.com/news/celebrity/mmx-timberlake_pmay30,0,7012709.story%3Fcoll%3Dmmx-celebrity_heds&cid=1116770876&ei=jv1eRsO-FY-oqgO5vv3PDQ Metromix. 'Sexy' singer has new label: CEO find it fast: search metromix.com find things to do 4,000 Chicago bars and clubs. PERSONALS: WHO'S WHO & WHAT'S UP 'Sexy' singer has new label: CEO Justin Timberlake plans to start his own label, a joint venture with Interscope Records called Tennman Records, E!Online reports. The "SexyBack" singer, who will be chairman and chief executive officer of the venture, says he has personally chosen artists for the label, according to E! "I cannot wait to introduce the world to my new discoveries," Timberlake said in a statement. Apparently he can wait, though, because he's not naming any names for a couple of weeks. Personals was compiled by Kim Profant from Tribune news services and staff reports Copyright & terms of service
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/16-5&fd=R&url=http://www.411mania.com/movies/film_reviews/55014/Pirates-of-the-Caribbean:-At-World%255C%255Cs-End-Review-%255B3%255D.htm&cid=1116836906&ei=jv1eRsO-FY-oqgO5vv3PDQ Pirates of the Caribbean: At World's End Review The Goodness: Wrestling Needs the Kids Paradigm Shift: The Wikipedia Revolution I'll Hit It!: MMA Goes Mainstream Chutes and Ladders: 27 and Under Club Angry Gaming: Your Next Gaming PC Pirates of the Caribbean: At World's End Review [3] Pirates of the Caribbean: At World's End Review [3] Hot Fuzz Review [2] Pirates of the Carribean 3 Pirates of the Caribbean: At World's End Review [3] Proof that even Johnny Depp can't work miracles. Pirates of the Caribbean: At Worlds End Ted Elliot and Terry Rossio Rated PG-13 for intense sequences of action/adventure violence and some frightening images. Ill be honest, Im somewhat at a loss as to how to review a movie like Pirates of the Caribbean: At Worlds End , for a couple reasons. First off, its not like any criticism leveled at it, from me or any other critic, is gonna stop everyone from seeing it. Id say Pirates of the Caribbean: Dead Mans Chest Secondly, I find my normal reviewing style somewhat useless with this film. As anyone who has read any of my previous reviews knows, I like to first write about the films story, and then spend a little time examining different individual aspects of the movie, like the directing, writing, acting, etc. But whats the point of that with a film like , when all people really care about is one thing. Oh sure, there will be the small contingent of young girls going to swoon over Orlando Bloom, and I know theres still that cluster of folks who just think anything involving pirates is cool (theyll be the ones dressed as pirates at the screenings). But, lets face it, nearly everyone else will be going for one reason, and one reason only: Captain Jack Sparrow. Perhaps then, I should just let you know the good, and bad, news. The good news is Johnny Depp is still compelling as always, his Capt. Jack remains one of cinemas most bizarre and engaging anti-heroes. The bad news is that, with this third film in the series, the makers of  own interest in Capt. Jack seems to be waning a little quicker than the audiences. At least, that appears to be the case, as Jack is essentially shoved aside and lost amidst an overwhelming cavalcade of twists, turns, character revelations, betrayals, red herrings, and, by the end of the whole thing, just flat-out audience exhaustion. It really is enough to make one pine for the simple, good-old-days of the first film, when we only had three or four parallel stories to follow. picks up shortly after the last films cliffhanger finale, with Will Turner (Bloom) and Elizabeth Swann (Kiera Knightley), now working together with the recently resurrected Captain Barbossa (Geoffrey Rush) and voodoo queen Tia Dalma (Naomie Harris), meeting with Captain Sao Feng, the pirate lord of Singapore (Chow Yun-Fat). It turns out Feng is in possession of a map that can help them rescue Jack from Davy Jones Locker, the afterlife he was condemned to after being swallowed by the monstrous Kraken  and what an afterlife it is, a sort-of purgatory where Jack is forced to captain a land-locked ship crewed by multiple versions of himself. Its completely insane and, thanks to the bonus Depps, one of the films most memorable scenes. Unfortunately, its somewhat downhill from there, as our heroes manage to escape this strange limbo and embark on their mission; namely, a gathering of the nine pirate lords, where they will decide how to deal with the threat posed by the East India Trading Company, now more powerful than ever thanks to a forced alliance with Davy Jones (Bill Nighy), who is none-too-happy to be following anyones orders. This story probably could have been kept simple, but instead it quickly spins wildly out of control, eventually buckling under the weight of its numerous sub-plots, not to mention its unnecessary two hour and 48 minute running time. Its arguable that the makers of these films have lost sight of what made the first film so enjoyable in the first place. At the end of the day, Pirates of the Caribbean: The Curse of the Black Pearl was nothing more than a simple, undemanding pirate/ghost story, something that hadnt been pulled offhell, even attempted, in years. But with , and now even more so , the writers, producers, and director appear uncertain that such a straightforward formula can keep the audiences interests through multiple films. I wish they had at least given it a shot. In my opinion, simplicity is not always a bad thing, and it probably would have been vastly superior to what we have been given instead. Rather than replicate the breathless, giddy exhilaration of the first film, the sequels creak awkwardly along, victims of a desire to establish their own Lord of the Rings -like mythology, complete with too many characters, too much back-story, and way too many undeveloped ideas. I thought , with its multiple storylines and characters, was too ambitious, but makes Raimis film look like is so bloated with extraneous elements, it sometimes seems like even the writers have lost track of it all  a strange and confusing scene in which a character mistakes Elizabeth for an ancient sea Goddess is never explained, nor resolved. Whats worse, the amazing sword fights and imaginative action scenes that graced the first two films are here sacrificed to make way for the far-too-many scenes of people talking, which are unfortunately necessary to constantly explain what the hell is going on. Dont get me wrong, the giant sea battle that makes up s climax is somewhat impressive, but also is a tad too CGI-reliant and impersonal to be all exciting, not to mention it has a definite been there, done that feeling. Some people complained that the three-way sword fight atop the giant rolling wheel in was superfluous and too over-the-top, but I would have killed for a scene that exciting in But perhaps no sin is more unforgivable than the bizarre decision to take the focus off of Sparrow. For all its characters and stories, the franchise has always rested almost entirely on Depps shoulders. And, to this point, he has risen admirably to the challenge, serving as the series beating heart, infusing the previous films with a madcap, devilish spirit. And yes, he does so again  whenever Jack is on screen the film noticeably regains some of its life, particularly in his hilarious exchanges with Rushs Captain Barbossa (without a doubt the series second best character  Rushs presence is definitely one of the few improvements over the last film). If theres any downside to Jack this time around its that he is no longer as new and fresh as he was the first time we saw him, and therefore his odd persona is no longer the delightful surprise it once was. Still, the character remains incredibly captivating, and Depp does a nice job reminding us why we fell in love with the franchise in the first place. How sad it is, then, to see Jack this time shunted off to the peripheral for a good portion of the film. Rather than being the driving force that moves the films many storylines along, Jack is here just another cog in the machine, one more character lost in a sea of confusion, overshadowed by the films unrelenting onslaught of ideas and revelations. Further exacerbating the problem is that, by taking the focus off of Jack, it means it's shifted more towards Elizabeth and Will, which only serves to remind us how boring these characters are. Elizabeths continuing transformation into a bad-ass warrior (and even eventually the leader of the pirates  I kid you not) is perhaps the films most unbelievable element  and Im talking about a movie that feature a man with tentacles for a beard. Plus, Knightleys pouty, sour-faced performance continues to betray the conceit of the character; you can never quite figure out why exactly so many of the male characters are in love with this girl (besides her looks of course, but Im trying to give the film some credit and not assume its shallow). Its as if Knightley is in some kind of unspoken competition with Kirsten Dunst to be this summers most allegedly-irresistible-but-in-fact-completely-unlikable movie heroine. As for Blooms Will Turner, he remains one of the blandest movie heroes in recent memory, and even this films reveal, that he is just as willing as the rest of the characters to backstab his friends for his own agenda, does little to change that. I remember hearing talk that the sequels would finally give Bloom something more interesting to do, and make his character more compelling. Turns out this is true, but, unfortunately, by the time this character change happens, and they finally figure out a way to make him interesting, the movie is nearly over. a complete lost cause? Not exactly. There are definitely some fun and unforgettable sequences sprinkled here and there, and I suppose it is kinda nice to finally see the saga achieve a sense of closure (somewhat). Plus, in all honesty, Id be lying if I said I probably wont end up buying this film on DVD someday. I am, after all, a completist, and Id hate to leave the first two films all alone on my shelf. Still, for a series that started so strong, its a shame to have to say that the third, and possibly final, film gets by on simply having a few good moments. Remember when the original film was first announced, and everyone the world over mocked Disney, claiming you cant make a good movie out of a theme park ride? Well, those folks were obviously wrong  you can make at least good movie out of a theme park ride. Its when it comes to extending the story that you obviously run into problems. So, will this be the end of the franchise? There are already conflicting statements from those involved with the series on whether this really is the last film or not. Personally, I would love to see more of Capt. Jack on the big screen, but after Im not too sure I want it to be in more Pirates of the Caribbean films. How about a Hope/Crosby-style road movie, with Jack and Barbossa? Or a movie where Jack is somehow zapped into our own modern times? Even better yet  Capt. Jack in space. Believe me, Id follow this character to the ends of the earth, but after seeing this third, waterlogged entry, I think its time to dry-dock this particular series for good. : To put it politely, Pirates of the Caribbean: At Worlds End is an overindulgent, though mildly entertaining, mess. It's even more bloated and overwhelming than the disappointing , with everything that made the first film so special pushed aside in favor of an unnecessarily elaborate and complex story. And while Johnny Depp remains as amusing as ever, and the return of Geoffrey Rushs Captain Barbossa raises the film a hair above the previous entry, even they can't save the movie from its own confusing mythology. Thanks to Depp, Rush, and a few fun sequences here and there, I wouldnt call it an unwatchable film. But its not all that great, either, and certainly doesnt live up to the promise the franchise originally showed. Lets just file this one under missed opportunity, and hope that if Capt. Jack ever returns to the screen, its in a film more befitting his character. Send Feedback to Trevor Snyder View Trevor Snyder's 411 Profile Email This Article To Your Friend --- More Reviews by Trevor Snyder --- Pirates of the Caribbean: At World's End Review [3] 28 Weeks Later Review [2] Spider-Man 3 Review [2] The Hitcher Review [2] Perfume: The Story of a Murderer Review The Texas Chainsaw Massacre: The Beginning Review [2] Snakes on a Plane Review [5] Mission: Impossible III Review --- All Reviews by Trevor Snyder --- --- More Articles by Trevor Snyder --- Pirates of the Caribbean: At World's End Review [3] The 411 Top 5: Week 62 The 411 Top 5: Week 6