http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/8-2&fd=R&url=http://seattlepi.nwsource.com/tv/317849_tv31.html&cid=1116730139&ei=jv1eRsO-FY-oqgO5vv3PDQ On TV: 'The Starter Wife' is pretty much a non-starter Skip ads and navigation Last updated May 30, 2007 5:32 p.m. PT On TV: 'The Starter Wife' is pretty much a non-starter It was probably only a matter of time before Gigi Levangie Grazer's "The Starter Wife" hit some screen, somewhere. For the benefit of those who don't recognize the name, Levangie Grazer is the wife of successful film producer Brian Grazer. She knows a little somethin'-somethin' about Hollywood ladies who lunch and fall from grace. Wrote a few books about it, even. Needless to say, a person could not reasonably expect a subject so tempting to remain on bookshelves unmolested for long. "The Starter Wife" came out in 2005; two summers later, USA Network is presenting it as a miniseries. One that proves that some books should never be anything more than books. What's riveting on the page has a tendency to transform into a bore or a mess on screens large or small. Doesn't matter if the novel's pulp or a Pulitzer Prize winner, it can stink either way. (Rent "Beloved." You'll see.) Chick lit like "The Starter Wife" poses a special danger because of its disposability. This is the kind of book meant to be left on airplanes or passed along to friends with the advisement that they don't need to be returned. There was really no need to drag Debra Messing, Joe Mantegna or Judy Davis into that pool. Alas, they're all in, along with Miranda Otto and blatant product placement of Pond's Time Rewind overnight cream -- Pond's being the major sponsor of this six-hour summertime event. A real Starter Wife would rather massage motor oil into her complexion than stoop to using drugstore brands; Crème de la Mer is as downscale as these ladies go. But never mind that. USA's "The Starter Wife" exists to delight women of a certain age, especially those who can relate to Molly Kagan's (Messing) situation. Molly is the perfect wife, attendant to the every need of her studio head husband (Peter Jacobson) until the morning he dumps her over the phone. We all know these things happen and, unlike a commoner's divorce, ends of rich people's marriages tend to be ameliorated by multimillion dollar settlements and endless trips to the spa. What we may not realize is what special hell awaits the less-powerful party in a Hollywood split. Sentencing for the jilted includes waiting forever for tables at the most exclusive restaurants; not being invited to weekend bacchanals at Brangelina's; having your charities dump you and former confidantes with names like Cricket (Otto) shun you. One also is forced to endure the icy glares of daring to exist after divorce makes you irrelevant. Oh, the staring. It's enough to make a woman frost her face with dollops of magical face cream (with dermal-recovery complex!) as if to ward off Molly's tortures. Molly finds respite in her boozy girlfriend Joan's (Davis) impeccably designed Malibu beach pad, and her interior-designer pal Rodney (Chris Diamantopoulos) helps pull her through the bleak lonely tunnel on the way to divorce court. It's probably unfair to say that flanking Messing's character with a rich drunkard and a gay husband is a throwback to "Will & Grace" but how can a person not notice? The memory of Karen Walker gives Joan the appeal of a tall glass of bitters. She may be a more honest TV alcoholic, which means she breaks things and suffers consequences, but Karen was loads more fun. Other pick-me-ups include Molly's soon-to-be-ex's business partner Lou (Mantegna), who swoops in at the right moments to remind Molly that she's still a woman, and a handsome mystery dude who spends all of his time on the beach. As it turns out, he's going through a rough spot, too. So is everyone else. All that glitters is not gold, you know. Blather and platitudes brought to life in a cable movie whose insubstantiality grows hour by hour. The essence of chick lit is well covered here -- fabulous woman and friends get toppled by circumstance, tumble down the hill together and land on the solid ground of True Selfhood. The formula for a decent, quick read. Television requires a different mix of stimulants absent in USA's muddled version. A sense of destination, solid plot progression and firmly developed story lines would all be nice. Director Jon Avnet ("Fried Green Tomatoes") should know that by now. But after Molly is dumped for a ditzy Britney-wannabe, the best "The Starter Wife" can do is a chronicle of adjustment to her debased circumstances, inch by inch. A mystery slapped into the story becomes after the fact thanks to a painfully stupid resolution. (And really, exile to Malibu? Certainly not the worst of fates.) A few days is all it takes to plow through Levangie Grazer's book, and it's easy to feel fine about that. Watching six hours of TV spread out over a few weeks is a lot to ask, especially given how disappointing, disorganized and disposable those installments shape up to be. "The Starter Wife" may best be enjoyed under optimal conditions, with the assistance of icy cocktails and the companionship of two or three great friends. That combination makes life's hardest situations bearable. You shouldn't need it to get your kicks out of a summer cable flick. 9 p.m. Thursdays, USA Network 'Wife' week continues with Lifetime's "Army Wives" and BBC America's "Footballers' Wives" P-I TV critic Melanie McFarland can be reached at 206-448-8015 or . Follow her TV Gal blog at What do you think? Add P-I TV headlines to TV & RADIO HEADLINES On TV: 'The Starter Wife' is pretty much a non-starter On Radio: More static for broadcasters: Now performers want royalties too Where Are They Now: Rod Belcher, former sports broadcaster Fall TV goes chic, revels in freaks and embraces its inner geek It wasn't a bomb that sent 350 state workers fleeing 'Friday' lights up small screen KOMO/4 unseats KING/5 at 11 p.m. Richie fears she may go to jail too Lovitz, Laugh Factory make lifelong deal Seat belt gaffe noted on 'Today' show Thompson won't be back on 'Law & Order' 'O.C.' star Barton Hospitalized Briefly Summertime folly: "Hidden Palms" debuts on The CW Two must-sees for a three-day weekend -- and yes, one of them is "Friday Night Lights." A finale potpourri, brought to you in lame haikus Economy nearly stalled in first quarter N.H. governor signs civil unions law Iraq residents rise up against al-Qaida Putin: U.S. has triggered new arms race Five cos. win gov't telecom contract Listener helps save ailing disc jockey Wal-Mart cashier: I was fired for joking Promotional fax mistaken for bomb threat Musician canned for focus on wrong organ Couple sue Wal-Mart over slip in vomit New breed of cat retails for $22,000 Dying vet planned a final mission 'Spam King' suspect seized Recent grads offer real-world perspective to Class of 2007 Pre-Draft Notebook: Halperin says 'no' to Sonics Microsoft Surface brings computing to the table Ancestry.com puts 90M war records online New breed of cat retails for $22,000 Where car thieves love to tread Dying vet planned a final mission A city with no Sonics: How life will change if NBA leaves Seattle Viaduct-free plan on the table $6 tolls proposed for new 520 Bridge Where car thieves love to tread Condo dwellers seek quieter life in new parts of city 101 Elliott Ave. W. Home Delivery: (206) 464-2121 or (800) 542-0820 seattlepi.com serves about 1.7 million unique visitors and 30 million page views each month. Send investigative tips to
