http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/11-6&fd=R&url=http://www.lacitybeat.com/article.php%3Fid%3D5583%26IssueNum%3D208&cid=1116822059&ei=jv1eRsO-FY-oqgO5vv3PDQ Brooks Brothers - Los Angeles CityBeat Sign up for our free Weird Scenes Inside the Goldmine How slumlord siblings trashed the iconic Morrison Hotel and how tenants fought back Bus and train fares will go up in July as activists threaten legal action Federal judge rules environmental monkeywrenchers can be sentenced as terrorists The noted bio-ethicist on Oudry, animal liberation, and jailing animal activists as terrorists Its the Water, Diversity City Cartoon By Ted Rall Photographs by Gary Leonard An unlikely marriage of movie and music bears Loudon Wainwright IIIs fine Strange Weirdos Attention Span Threatened by Advancing Minisodes! Macy Gray reignites her eccentric, epic soul and psychedelic funk at the Key Club Costner experiences a world of Hurt in new thriller ~ LATEST REVIEWS ~ ~ SPECIAL SCREENINGS ~ ~ NOW PLAYING ~ Howard Hawkss classic remains one of the greatest Westerns ever A new book celebrates the true artistry of a pseudo 60s soul legend A Bark in the Dark Dog deserves an audience as it gambles on a bigger venue ~ ROCK, POP, ACOUSTIC ~ ~ JAZZ, BLUES, LATIN ~ ~ COMEDY CLUBS ~ ~ ART OPENINGS ~ ~ READINGS, ETC. ~ ~ GIVE IT UP! ~ A Diner Maintains its Difference Wons Coffee Shop serves eclectic Chinese-American fare in an old-time setting Costner experiences a world of Hurt in new thriller ~ By ANDY KLEIN ~ Photo by Ben Glass ~ The thing with Two Heads: Hurt and Costner emulating Ray Milland and Rosie Grier ~ he good news is: There are no sequels or threquels this week. The bad news is: That rules out a whole class of easy wiseass putdowns (Shrek the Third is a third as good as the first! The new Pirates of the Caribbean is so bad it makes the last Pirates of the Caribbean look like the first Pirates of the Caribbean!). The medium news is: The new Kevin Costner thriller, Mr. Brooks, while unsatisfying in some ways, is interesting enough that I wont have to use my overworked invective muscle. The film dives right into its central premise with an opening title card of the sort usually saved for epigrams from the Book of Revelation: The hunger has returned to Mr. Brooks brain. It never left really. We meet Earl Brooks (Costner) as he is being honored at a testimonial dinner. This self-made pillar of the community is a wealthy businessman, husband to luscious Emma (Marg Helgenberger), loving father to college girl Jane (Danielle Panabaker, whom I mistook for Amber Tamblyn until the credits rolled), philanthropist, all-around great guy. But even as he is feted by the outside world, he is fetid on the inside. Like so many others, Earl has an addiction problem  except his addiction is to killing. (Together with the upcoming You Kill Me, this is one of two movies this month to show murderers attending AA meetings. Go figure.) Even as hes driving home from the dinner, his control begins to slip. Someone named Marshall (William Hurt) materializes in the back seat of the car and starts goading Earl to have a little fun. Director/co-writer Bruce A. Evans is as unambiguous as possible about Marshall. At his very first appearance, its crystal clear that he couldnt have been hiding in the back; that Emma, in the front passenger seat, cant see him or hear him; and that Emma cant even hear Earls side of the exchange. That is, Marshall definitely exists only in Earls mind. You might argue that hes some sort of possessing demon, but he has no visibility outside of Earls p.o.v. (unlike, to use the most obvious example, the evil spirit BOB in Twin Peaks). Once home, Earl tells Emma he wants to stay up and work, which tonight means murdering someone, aided by his imaginary confidante. But, this time around, Earl and Marshall are a little careless. (Or is some part of Earls psyche trying to get caught?) He is spotted in the house by one of the victims neighbors, an amateur photographer we only know initially as Mr. Smith (Dane Cook). Luckily, Mr. Smith is just as twisted as Earl, and arguably less sympathetic. An obnoxious geek, Smith doesnt give his evidence to the cops, but rather uses it to blackmail Earl into taking him along on his next killing, because, hey, what could be cooler than that? At the same time, police detective Atwood (Demi Moore) is hot on the trail of the perpetrator, while dealing with her own convoluted set of issues. Atwood has an excess of back story  she grew up as a super-rich kid and is still in competition with her intimidating father; shes in the middle of an ugly divorce; and another evil psycho she nailed has just broken out of jail and is looking for payback. The films central idea  Mr. Right being secretly Evil  is not precisely new. In literary terms, the concept goes back to Robert Louis Stevenson; Earl is basically the altogether virtuous Dr. Jekyll, with Marshall his partially released Mr. Hyde. Whats interesting in Evanss approach is the low-key expression of this classic concept. That is, after his delightful over-the-top performance in A History of Violence, one might have expected Hurt to chew the scenery. In fact, he has rarely been more restrained. Costner has always done his most interesting work when he strays furthest from his Jimmy Stewart/Gary Cooper persona. (Note: Im using that as fuzzy shorthand, since, as fans are aware, both of those actors played characters with really disturbing dark sides, particularly Stewart.) In a film like The Postman, Costner seems too protective of his aw-shucks good-guy image; hes much better in Clint Eastwoods A Perfect World, where he isnt straitjacketed in a heroic mode. And in the much-maligned 3000 Miles to Graceland, he plays a downright villain, and he seems to be enjoying it. The fact is, there has always been a neurotic, scary edge to Costner that he generally suppresses. His endearing grin has just a touch of the manic, and hes at his best when he gives it freer rein  which is what he does here. Earl Brooks may be a tragic  or at least sad  figure, but there are moments when Costner gives him a face that is crazier and more wicked than anything we see from Marshall. Also keeping the movie interesting is a truly ugly subcurrent in the story  I cant be explicit without major spoilage  that is only slightly hinted at. Or perhaps its just my David Lynch-soaked mind seeing horror where none is intended. Despite its virtues, Mr. Brooks begins to flag before its two hours are up. Evans and partner Raynold Gideon throw in so much plot that things get muddled. The final working out of all the different threads is downright confusing, smacking of last-minute doctoring or trimming an overlong running time. Speaking of plot confusion  In my sporadic, after-the-fact attempts to figure out just who in Pirates of the Caribbean: At Worlds End, was doing what to whom (and why?) it suddenly occurred to me that this Bloated, Disappointing Third Episode in a Trilogy had amazing similarities to perhaps the all-time champion Bloated, Disappointing Third Episode in a Trilogy. Think about it: The hero is trapped in a mystical, white holding area. Out in the real world, his friends are trying to free him. They need charts or instructions to bridge the gap between the worlds. They boldly show up at the headquarters of a foreign adversary (of dubious reliability), who has what they need, leading to a big fracas. Meanwhile, the film is stretched out to excessive length by endless new plot complications, interminable CGI battles, and more and more supernatural rules that correlate to nothing real but must be accepted just because. Is it Pirates of the Caribbean: At Worlds End? Or is it The Matrix Revolutions? Would anybody consciously choose the Wachowski Brotherss mess as a template to emulate? Perhaps the similarities end there. It would take another viewing of both films to find further common elements. And thats a sacrifice Im not currently willing to make. Mr. Brooks. Directed by Bruce A. Evans. Written by Bruce A. Evans & Raynold Gideon. With Kevin Costner, Demi Moore, Dane Cook, William Hurt, Marg Helgenberger, Ruben Santiago-Hudson, and Danielle Panabaker. Opens Friday citywide. &copy; 2007 Southland Publishing, All Rights Reserved. Development and Hosting
