http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/2i-0&fd=R&url=http://www.accesshollywood.com/news/ah5380.shtml&cid=1116125302&ei=jv1eRsO-FY-oqgO5vv3PDQ Access Hollywood | Chauffeur Testifies He Saw Gun In Phil Spector's Hand | Celebrity and Hollywood News Skip to Main Content Celebrity and Hollywood News Chauffeur Testifies He Saw Gun In Phil Spector's Hand LOS ANGELES (May 16, 2007) -- Phil Spector's chauffeur testified Wednesday that he fled the music producer's home after seeing his boss with a gun and the body of an actress inside -- and feared he could have been shot himself. Adriano De Souza returned to the stand in Spector's murder trial a day after telling the jury how he heard a "pow" as he waited outside Spector's castle-like home on Feb. 3, 2003. He said Spector emerged with a gun in hand and said, "I think I killed somebody." Prosecutor Alan Jackson showed the jury photographs of Lana Clarkson's body slumped in a chair in the foyer and close-up of her face with blood around her mouth. The defense claims she shot herself. De Souza said he saw Clarkson's body slumped in a chair with her legs near the floor and asked Spector what happened, to which Spector responded with a shrug. "I didn't know what to do," De Souza testified. "I tried to escape from that place. ... He could shoot me." De Souza said he started to run, then remembered the car and drove outside of the gate. He said he used his cell phone to call Spector's secretary, where he left a message, then called 911. "I think my boss killed somebody," he told one operator in a tape of the call played in court. Asked why he thought that, he stammered, "Because ... he, he have a lady on the, on the floor and he have a gun in, in his hand." He was transferred to a police department and had a conversation with an officer while waiting for authorities to arrive. He spoke of his fear during the conversation, saying, "I'm not inside anymore. I'm afraid to go inside," to which the officer responded, "I don't want you to, OK?" De Souza said he called the secretary first to get Spector's exact street address, and he stopped outside the estate's gate because the address was on a sign there. De Souza, an immigrant from Brazil whose native language is Portuguese, speaks in accented English and the defense has questioned how well he understood Spector. Initial cross-examination by the defense focused on his English education and immigration status. De Souza told the prosecutor he clearly understood Spector. On Tuesday, De Souza described driving Spector and Clarkson from the House of Blues to the producer's house. Clarkson was reluctant, but agreed to join Spector for one drink, De Souza said. Spector rose to fame in the 1960s and '70s, changing rock music with what became known as the "Wall of Sound" recording technique. Clarkson was best known for a role in the 1985 film "Barbarian Queen." . All rights reserved. This material may not be published, broadcast, rewritten or redistributed. Your email address: * Recipient's email address: * Add a personal message: Spector Murder Trial Testimony: He 'Was Not His Usual Self' 'Police Had Murder On Their Mind' Says Phil Spector's Attorney Prosecutors Call Phil Spector 'Sinister & Deadly' Phil Spector's Murder Trial: A Long History Of Gun Violence? Jury Selection In Phil Spector Trial Focuses On Celebs Jury Selection To Begin In Phil Spector Murder Trial Phil Spector Murder Trial To Be Televised Phil Spector Murder Trial To Be Televised? Jury Selection Begins In Phil Spector Murder Trial Producer Phil Spector's Murder Trial Delayed Again &copy; NBC Universal, 2007, all rights reserved Subscribe To Our RSS
