http://www.mercurynews.com/columns/ci_6026681&cid San Jose Mercury News - McCollum: `Starter Wife' is the perfect summertime fluff san jose / valley start / stop paper (From the last 24 hours) Prosecutors: Aptos woman lived high life on &#36;1.5 million stolen... ACLU targets planner of so-called CIA torture flights Kawakami: Bryant reveals a tortured soul Spector defense targets forensic errors Rivals Steve Jobs, Bill Gates talk like old pals McCollum: `Starter Wife' is the perfect summertime fluff Article Launched: 05/31/2007 01:33:26 AM PDT When it came out in May 2005, Gigi Levangie Grazer's made a splash as the consummate beach book. A Hollywood roman a(gra) clef, it had all the right stuff for summer success: It was fluffy, unchallenging, sexy, glitzy and eminently readable. Now, cable's USA has turned "Starter Wife" into the television equivalent of beach lit. The six-hour miniseries, which begins at 9 tonight, is fluffy, unchallenging, sexy (in a basic-cable way), glitzy and so eminently watchable (and well-made) that it transcends the concept of guilty pleasure. While some of the book's details have been altered in the transition to TV, the key elements remain the same. Molly (Debra Messing) is the 40-ish wife of film studio executive Kenny Kagan (Peter Jacobson in one of the most thankless roles of the season), who dumps her in favor of a Britney Spears-esque pop singer. All of a sudden, Molly's good life - the fab lunches, premieres and parties - is gone, and she is a social outcast in that peculiar, status-driven world known as Hollywood. Molly does have some support. There's gay designer Rodney (Chris Diamantopoulos, Jason Barone on "The Sopranos") and best friend Joan (Judy Davis of "Judy Garland: Me and My Shadows," in a scenery-chewing performance of epic proportions), who loans her a house in the Malibu Colony while Joan herself is off in rehab. A security guard at the Colony (Anika Noni Rose of "Dreamgirls") provides some grounded perspective on Molly's problems, while her soon-to-be ex-husband's boss - studio head Lou Manahan (Joe Mantegna) - and local beach boy Sam (Stephen Moyer of "Uprising") provide a little male companionship along the way. It's all pretty lightweight stuff, and it's unlikely you're going to be moved by Molly's anguish over being bounced from the A list. But much of the dialogue, by writers Sara Parriott and Josann McGibbon ("Runaway Bride"), is smart, sassy and knowing, and director Jon Avnet ("Boomtown") has given the miniseries a bright, snappy look. But the best part of "Starter Wife" is a very engaging performance by Messing, who drops all her "Will & Grace" tics and tricks in favor of a more natural acting style. She's utterly charming, particularly when matched up with Mantegna, who provides some dramatic oomph. At six hours, "Starter Wife" is hardly a "quick read," and there are some rough patches along the way. But it's a perfectly fine summer diversion, and that's OK. (10 p.m. Sunday) falls into another literary genre: chick-lit. A cross between "Desperate Housewives" and the home front part of CBS's "The Unit," it feels like something that would have fit nicely into ABC's lineup of female-skewing dramas. Based on Tanya Biank's "Under Sabres: The Unwritten Code of Army Wives," the series is a prime-time soap that just happens to be set on a military base. Four wives with more than a few marital problems and lot of those pesky secrets provide the focal point, while lovers, husbands and other strangers swirl around the fringes. While lacking the satirical humor of "Housewives" and the edge of "Unit," the show is serviceable in its storytelling, quite well-done in its production and better than well-done in its acting. Kim Delaney ("NYPD Blue") is more on her game than she has been in quite some time as the wife of a ranking officer; Brigid Brannagh ("Over There") is engaging as an ex-cop turned Army spouse; and stage actress Sally Pressman gives a sharp and spunky performance as a bartender who gets a quickie marriage to a young soldier. Lifetime is in the process of trying to upgrade the quality of its original series - it has two more debuting this summer - and "Army Wives" isn't a bad start. I suppose it was inevitable that TV eventually would jump on the "Pirates of the Caribbean" ship and give us a television version of the pirate's life. (8 tonight, Chs. 5, 46) is produced by Mark Burnett of "Survivor" and is basically that show set on pirate ship. There are 16 contestants going through 33 days of elimination challenges to try for the big booty of &#36;1 million. Sound familiar&#63; Arrr! Now that NBC renewed despite low viewership for its first season, the network is re-airing episodes of this marvelous drama on Sundays (9 p.m., Chs. 8, 11). This week's is one of the series' better installments, as star running back Smash Williams (Gaius Charles) gets involved with performance-enhancing drugs, and Tim Riggins (a very good Taylor Kitsch) and Lyla Garrity (Minka Kelly) start their rather messy affair. Contact Charlie McCollum at cmccollum@mercurynews.com or (408)920-5245. His TV blog appears at http://blogs .mercurynews.com/aei The Mercury News is pleased to let readers post comments about an article at the end of the article. Please increase the credibility of your post by including your full name and city when commenting. Sorry, no items are currently available. Copyright 2007 San Jose Mercury News Privacy Policy and Terms of Use MNG Corporate Site Map
