http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/16-2&fd=R&url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/film/article1860582.ece&cid=1116836906&ei=jv1eRsO-FY-oqgO5vv3PDQ Any parent who sat through two hours and 47 minutes of Pirates of the Caribbean: At World&rsquo;s End last weekend, family in tow, will have momentarily thought of leaping into the giant whirlpool during the fim&rsquo;s climactic battle scene. Well, here&rsquo;s the rub: expect more." /> Three-hours and counting &ndash; the future of film-making -Arts & Entertainment-Film-TimesOnline Our exclusive four-step guide to giving up before the ban Navigation - link to other main sections from here Vaughan&rsquo;s position in the side no longer needs questioning Three-hours and counting &ndash; the future of film-making to not show photographer information --> to not show image description --> here with the id "dynamic-image-navigation" is used so that the innerHTML can be written to by the JS call below. --> Any parent who sat through two hours and 47 minutes of Pirates of the Caribbean: At World&rsquo;s End last weekend, family in tow, will have momentarily thought of leaping into the giant whirlpool during the fim&rsquo;s climactic battle scene. Well, here&rsquo;s the rub: expect more. The producer Jerry Bruckheimer recently said that there was life in the tired trilogy yet, even without Johnny Depp as Captain Jack Sparrow. &ldquo;This is the end [of the trilogy], but whether one of the characters or a couple of the characters continue on, it&rsquo;s a possibility,&rdquo; said the Top Gunproducer. &ldquo;Certainly, in a moment at the end of the film there is a hope that something else might happen.&rdquo; Surely some mistake? Already, fourth, fifth and sixth Pirates movies seem an inevitability. And, while the money rolls in &ndash; Pirates 3, currently showing in 102 countries, earned &pound;63.2 million over its opening three days &ndash; it&rsquo;s easy to see Disney&rsquo;s logic. That said, the patience of parents everywhere is wearing thin. Blockbusters, like lawn dogs in the summer, are getting worryingly obese. The recent Spider-Man 3, complete with twists and turns and multiple endings, clocked in at two hours and 20 minutes. Perhaps it&rsquo;s time to reboot the thinking behind blockbuster franchises. Back in 1999, Toy Story, one of the the most successful films, clocked in at only 81 minutes. And the sequel, Toy Story 2? Just 91 minutes. Sometimes, just sometimes, less is undoubtedly more. * Town / City Save to my times One last drop in the Ocean? How Water can go up in flames Also in Arts & Entertainment Lord of the Rings show postponed after actor stage injury The artist who went to the movies Our drawing challenge winners&rsquo; Tate day out Museum brings dinosaurs on board Noah&rsquo;s Ark Fans tired of special effects, says Pullman epic director Pirates of the Caribbean What you thought of Spider-Man 3 The entire theater broke out into sustained applause as the credits ran at the end Including Ocean's Thirteen, starring Brad, George and Matt Daaaamon The gripping tale of a manhunt that turned into an obsession Info on the latest screenings, film offers and competitions from The Times, The Sunday Times and Times Online &ndash; all in one place. News, reviews and video from Cannes Video interview with acclaimed director Shane Meadows She relied on an oxygen machine. The electricity firm cut off the power. Hours later she was dead The nation&rsquo;s top ten players - no arguments United sign Hargreaves to leave rivals standing She relied on an oxygen machine. The electricity firm cut off the power. Hours later she was dead Creationist museum brings dinosaurs on board Noah&rsquo;s Ark Why heroic Ruth should have been in Gordon&rsquo;s book United sign Hargreaves to leave rivals standing American attempt to patent yoga puts Indians in a twist Beware of 3-D &#150; it&rsquo;ll have your eye out Greek treasures get a lift to their new home