http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/14-1&fd=R&url=http://www.thestar.com/entertainment/article/219642&cid=1116799715&ei=jv1eRsO-FY-oqgO5vv3PDQ TheStar.com - entertainment - Arrrrr, it's a hard life on TV Full Text Article Archive TheStar.com - entertainment - Arrrrr, it's a hard life on TV Arrrrr, it's a hard life on TV May 31, 2007 04:30 AM The life of a pirate: is there anything more horrifying? There you are, adrift on the choppy seas, trying to keep down the bowl of gruel you choked back for lunch. To your left, rumpled rogues in their sun-bleached tricorns and tattered Elizabethan frills. To your right, mumbling reprobates, each one smellier and less toothy than the next. While deciphering cryptic maps to the buried treasure, you want to scratch your head. But you can't because your hand is a hook. Then there's the damn ship, which always needs work. And the captain, an unintelligible tyrant even when he's not sauced on grog. To top it off, you misplaced your eyepatch during the last plunder. The last lady who made your acquaintance had scurvy. And after the banana incident, now even the monkey hates your guts. Heavenly freedom? More like a living hell. So leave it to Mark Burnett &ndash; the wily buccaneer of network television who remains in constant search of prime-time booty &ndash; to burnish this pirate mythology, attach a &#34;reality&#34; mast and sail it into our living rooms this summer. (CBS, CTV, 8 tonight) is essentially on a barque. That is, 16 contestants are garbed in period costumes, tossed into longboats and encouraged to row toward a 179-foot ship, their home for 33 days. These poor idiots &ndash; sorry, &#34;modern day pirates&#34; &ndash; will drift near Dominica, in the Caribbean, searching for hidden loot. They'll also backstab, butt heads and throw elbows during story arcs inflamed with interpersonal conflict, the hallmark of Burnett Productions. &#34;This is really a step back in history where 16 lucky Americans get to live as pirates &ndash; Arrr!&#34; says Burnett, sounding more like Jonny Quest than Johnny Depp. As per usual, the motivating factor in this manufactured lunacy is the promise of riches; during the &#34;expeditions,&#34; contestants will search for chests of gold coin. Meaning, instead of a $1 million jackpot during a finale few may watch &ndash; Burnett's is quickly becoming a small-screen bomb &ndash; the rewards will be doled out weekly. The contestants will also elect a captain, unaware this will immediately create a caste system on the barque. The captain, you see, will get most of the treasure. And he/she will select two officers. These three will live in relative luxury. Everybody else will be relegated to servant status. As Burnett explained in one preview: &#34;What makes this series really pop is the democracy element on the ship.&#34; What does that mean? It means Burnett is basically plagiarizing himself. Because, again, the parallels between are painfully obvious, starting with the alliances, deals and ever present threat of mutiny. Instead of Tribal Council, there'll be a Pirate's Court. Instead of an extinguished torch there'll be a metaphorical walking of the plank. And instead of Jeff Probst, there'll be Cameron Daddo, a host who makes up for his lack of dimples with foreign-born optimism: &#34;What's going to suck people in about this show is the romance of the sea!&#34; Pirates have always held certain sway within popular culture, from The Pirates of Penzance to Disney's wildly successful Pirates of the Caribbean That franchise, based on a theme-park ride, has triggered more drooling in Hollywood than a T-bone steak inside a dog pound. So you can see why Burnett and CBS have high hopes for this high seas project. The key to its success will be a strong start, beginning with tonight's premiere. Because if viewers miss the boat, they probably won't be inclined to catch up with these pirates. Conrad Black on trial Great home delivery subscription deals here! 