http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/13-3&fd=R&url=http://www.mercurynews.com/news/ci_6057918&cid=1116125302&ei=h4BkRteEHIL0rQO9rMChBg Newsletters & Email Deals Help - Frequently Asked Questions To protect your account, please sign in. Not a member yet? Keep me signed in on this computer until I sign out. You must accept or we cannot save your information. Copyright 2007 San Jose Mercury News Privacy Policy and Terms of Use
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/6-3&fd=R&url=http://www.niagarafallsreporter.com/calleri6.5.07.html&cid=1116968833&ei=h4BkRteEHIL0rQO9rMChBg Niagara Falls Reporter Review SCREEN SCENE: RAUNCH RULES IN RANCID 'KNOCKED UP' Look, here's the deal. I absolutely refuse to throw in the towel. OK, you have every right to ask: What towel? Call me foolhardy, call me naive, but I still believe that the romantic movie comedy is not dead or even dying. However, after watching "Knocked Up," I have every right to believe that it's on life support. I will admit to laughing at some of the jokes in the film. There are some funny lines, many of them spoken with a deliciously jaundiced attitude. But I can honestly state that I did not laugh at the gags that were crude, vulgar and, yes, even obscene. I'm no prude and I've seen thousands of movies, many of which were awful. But there's something about taking a genre -- the romantic fable -- and turning it into sludge that really riles me. Some background is in order. There's a gang of writers and actors in Hollywood that personify the frat-boy mentality. Whether any of them were actually in fraternities, I don't know. These men who refuse to grow up gave us "The 40-Year-Old Virgin," some other movie efforts and a few television shows. The primary male behind the aforementioned film is writer-director Judd Apatow. He was lucky to have Steve Carell in that feature, because the actor brought not only his wry way of speaking but also his deadpan looks. Apatow has now written and directed "Knocked Up," and somewhere along the line he's confused himself with the directing legends of movie comedy -- Billy Wilder, Preston Sturges, Frank Capra, to name but three. Apatow is no genius. He has a way with filth, and that's not anything for which to be grateful. You have every right to ask why I thought the lowbrow "Borat" was brilliant and the movie under discussion is not. That's because "Borat" wasn't presented as something it isn't. The comedy was character-driven. In Apatow's world, the comedy relies on lewd language, a twisted obsession with women's breasts (referred to throughout as "boobs") and a distorted view of male bonding. Does Apatow actually have so low an opinion of friendship that he believes men can only relate to each other by commenting on flatulence, gynecological implements and scoring with hot chicks? These are losers, any way you cut it. And why do we have to spend more than two hours watching a pack of losers, none of whom we'd want as friends? The movie is demeaning not only to women, but also to men. "Knocked Up" wants to think it's a romantic comedy, even while it subverts the formula. Yes, you absolutely can have fun with the genre, but you can't turn it into a cesspool and pretend you're making something worthwhile. This is not a movie for children, nor is it for teenagers under 17. I don't even think Chris Rock has used the "F" word as much as it's spoken in this misfire. To top it off, we have to watch an "actor," and I use the word loosely, named Seth Rogen, who, as Ben, is every annoying slob who ever ate an entire bucket of chicken wings and asked for more. You've seen these guys; you know these guys. Television has prepared us for the overweight, marginally employed bum who's married to a truly beautiful woman, but should people really pay to see a T-shirt-wearing jerk act as if he actually cares about being a father? Rogen is such a bad performer that he can't carry it off. Here's the story: Ben beds Alison, a stunning blonde, played by Katherine Heigl, an actress I like. The two are both drunk, and soon graphic on-screen sex ensues. If I were a woman and this pig were lying on top of me, I'd vomit. But Apatow has her boozed up and not thinking clearly, which is an understatement. What about condoms, you ask? There is some comic by-play about the condom, but if one is used, there is no movie. Alison ends up pregnant. Her character works in television, and having a baby is definitely going to cramp her style. But her real crisis is not so much having the baby but having it with Ben around for the maternity ride. He suddenly becomes a different Ben -- Dr. Benjamin Spock -- and I guess we're supposed to care that he's so nurturing. It's a false sincerity. The impending baby is the only thing that gives his life meaning. Thus Alison is facing a life with two babies, one of whom is an adult who doesn't seem to understand that promising to change diapers isn't a monumental decision. A job would be nice. Alison has a married sister (an uninteresting Leslie Mann) who provides loads of advice. Paul Rudd is her husband, and you're relieved that he and Heigl are in the film. They give the goings-on a professional sheen that's sorely lacking. Ben is surrounded by a raunchy, annoying Greek chorus of male friends, each more boob-obsessed than the next. "Knocked Up" is an ode to laziness that runs on longer than is tolerable. It's clear that Apatow had no ending, so he kept adding extraneous scenes in hopes that one would click. The one he chose doesn't really click. If you go, enjoy the pop culture references and the work from Heigl and Rudd. Just be prepared for filthy dialogue that wants to be taken seriously. The female point-of-view isn't given intelligent -- or even comic -- consideration. At least Apatow doesn't think he's doing satire. Sadly, it seems as if he really believes in the drivel he's delivering. E-mail Michael Calleri at
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/17-5&fd=R&url=http://www.nbc5.com/news/13440066/detail.html&cid=1116966251&ei=h4BkRteEHIL0rQO9rMChBg Chicago Woman Gets Richest Divorce Settlement Ever - News Story - WMAQ | Chicago Monday, June 4, 2007, 4:13 pm Take a quick look at the day's top stories and weather forecast. Sign Up For E-Mail News Alerts IMAGES IN THE NEWS This Week's Celeb Birthdays Paris Hilton In LA Jail House Of Filth Shut Down Prosecutor: Man Admits Strangling Newlywed Couple Charged With Human Trafficking Teacher Of Year Faces Student Sex Charges 'Sopranos' Hit List: Who's Been Whacked (Spoiler Warning) The Week's Best Celebrity Photos Shouldn't Their 15 Minutes Be Up? Chicago Woman Gets Richest Divorce Settlement Ever $184 Million Awarded To Energy Magnate's Wife POSTED: 3:21 pm CDT June 4, 2007 Sign Up for Breaking News Alerts A Chicago woman was awarded $184 million Monday in what could be the richest divorce verdict in U.S. history. At the center of the legal dispute is energy magnate Michael Polsky and his wife of 31 years Maya Polsky. A Cook County judge awarded Maya Polsky $176 million in cash and assets in October. The figure represents half of the couple's estate. On Monday, the judge amended the figure to nearly $184 million because previously omitted assets increased the overall value of the estate. Maya Polsky's lawyers said she was her husband's confidant and should be considered a partner in his success. If it stands, the award would be a record in Illinois. The American Academy of Matrimonial Lawyers says it knows of no bigger award nationally. Michael Polsky's attorney said he plans to appeal the ruling. . All rights reserved. This material may not be published, broadcast, rewritten or redistributed. Quick & Easy Recipes Recipes From South Of The Border! Looking to add some culture to your dinner table? Spice up your meal with some of these Mexican favorites! Patrol Finds Bones In Car On Lake Bottom Murder-Suicide Suspected In Elderl