http://www.zap2it.com/tv/news/zap-themlivesatfox,0,3260871.story%3Fcoll%3Dzap-news-headlines&cid 'Battlestar' Producer's 'Them' Lives at FOX - James D'Arcy, Ben Feldman, Rachel Nichols and Tricia Helfer starred in the pilot - Zap2it Most E-mailed Stories &raquo; 'Battlestar' Producer's 'Them' Lives at FOX James D'Arcy, Ben Feldman, Rachel Nichols and Tricia Helfer starred in the pilot The aliens-among-us drama "Them" may not have made FOX's schedule for the fall, but the pilot appears not to be dead just yet. Talking to reporters on Friday (June 1) about the impending demise of Sci Fi Channel's "Battlestar Galactica," David Eick, co-creator/executive producer of the "Them" pilot, revealed that the show may still be in play. "It's not dead," Eick revealed. "They are talking to us about perhaps spending money on it and trying things and getting it into play I guess for midseason. All I know is it's still in play and something the network is very actively talking about. We'll know more in the next weeks and months." There's ample precedent for FOX opting to redevelop rejected pilots after-the-fact. Last season, for example, the network put "Drive" on the air at midseason after recasting and reshooting the initial pilot. Eick wrote the "Them" pilot with John McNamara ("Eyes"). Jonathan Mostow ("Breakdown") directed. Based on the graphic novel by Michael Avon Oeming and Daniel Berman, the series focused on government efforts to break up a sleeper cell of aliens operating out of Los Angeles. The pilot features James D'Arcy, Ben Feldman, Rachel Nichols and "Battlestar Galactica" veteran Tricia Helfer. "Battlestar" is currently shooting its fourth season in Vancouver. Producers on the Peabody Award-winning series announced last week that the 22-episode season will be its last. Even if FOX doesn't end up bringing "Them" to series, Eick should be able to stay busy. He's one of the producers on NBC's "Bionic Woman" revamp. Pick your favorite channels Customize our TV listings 