http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/11-1&fd=R&url=http://www.ksl.com/%3Fnid%3D148%26sid%3D1303922&cid=1116772926&ei=h4BkRteEHIL0rQO9rMChBg ksl.com - Advertisers Getting Creative to Beat Out the DVRs Paul Nelson Reporting [1:40] Advertisers Getting Creative to Beat Out the DVRs June 4th, 2007 @ 10:47am Paul Nelson, KSL Newsradio More people are finding ways to ignore commercials during their favorite shows, and that has advertisers nervous. So, how are they trying to adjust? It's one of the selling points of Tivo or a DVR (digital video recorder) system. You can record your favorite shows and fast forward through any annoying commercials. So, how many people do this? A recent report from Nielsen Media Research says 17 percent of all American homes have a digital recorder, and 60 percent of those people skip through ads. How many times would people say they stop and rewind to see a commercial they like? One person answers, "Once in a great while, I'll go back and watch a commercial, but it's rare." So, what are advertising executives doing to make this rare commercial that people actually want to watch? Well, for one thing, some of them are trying to make commercials look less like commercials. "There is this trend of creating a mini-drama or a mini-comedy series, so if you see one spot, you want to see the continuation of that spot. You want to see the ext phase of it," says Richter 7's Partner Peggy Lander. She says the old methods of advertising as we know them are slowly dying and that people are using web services and sites like youtube.com to filter which ads they want to see. The rest, they ignore. "Sometimes advertisers kill us with frequency. The message isn't creative, it isn't compelling but if we see it enough, it's going to make a difference. We're going to notice their product," Lander says. According to Lander, "Some commercials are so bad they actually get attention, too." She says sometimes advertisers make lame looking commercials just so we'll talk about how lame they are. Along with these mini-dramas or comedies, some networks are holding mini contests during commercial breaks. Court TV is expected to come out with a mini-mystery where someone could win $25,000. The only clues to the mystery come during the commercial breaks. Ads by 24 7 Real Media KSL Television & Radio, Salt Lake City UT EEO Public File Report A Division of Bonneville International m16 KSL's public inspection files, including the Children's Television Programming Reports, are available for viewing during regular office hours at the KSL Broadcast House.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/16-6&fd=R&url=http://www.nypost.com/seven/06042007/entertainment/theater/new_abts_is_a_sleeping_ugly_theater_clive_barnes.htm&cid=1116948888&ei=h4BkRteEHIL0rQO9rMChBg NEW ABT&#39;S IS A SLEEPING UGLY By CLIVE BARNES - Theater | Broadway Shows | Musicals Monday, June 04, 2007 Last Update: 05:10 PM EDT NEW ABT&#39;S IS A SLEEPING UGLY June 4, 2007 -- THE first three perform ances, over the week end, of American Ballet Theatre&#39;s brand-new version of "The Sleeping Beauty" started out skirting total disaster and ended, simply through superior dancing, with the occasional whiff of triumph. Unquestionably this new staging - with a team headed by Kevin McKenzie, the company&#39;s artistic director; Gelsey Kirkland, the former ballerina, and Michael Chernov, a dramaturge - provides less than a dim shadow of the 1890 masterpiece by choreographer Marius Petipa and composer Pyotr Tchaikovsky. Most of Tchaikovsky&#39;s score is there, some even added, but only the most famous bits of Petipa&#39;s choreography remain, including, blessedly intact, the entire dance text for the ballerina, Aurora. It is, of course, like producing "Hamlet," leaving Hamlet&#39;s role untouched, but having the story slightly adapted and the verse largely rewritten by overambitious stage managers. Even after reading the synopsis, the story now doesn&#39;t make much sense, while Tony Walton&#39;s settings and Willa Kim&#39;s costumes - both doubtless costing more than meets the eye - are as appropriately provincial as you might find in Omsk, Tomsk or some other whistle-stop on the Trans-Siberian railway. This is vastly inferior in concept, authority, dance text and even design to both the two earlier ABT stagings, the Skeaping/Messel in 1976 and the MacMillan/Georgiadis in 1987. The acting now is horrifyingly "motivated" as if the entire cast was auditioning for a German expressionist silent movie. This is hardly Petipa, even if the style of the dancing is generally more authentic. In the first-night cast, Marcelo Gomes as Prince Desire and especially Veronika Part as Aurora proved very disappointing, letting the evening subside around them like melting blancmange, although an undeterred Herman Cornejo flew high and mighty as the Bluebird. Both of Saturday&#39;s casts were a great deal better - Gillian Murphy, as Aurora in the evening, was a paragon of technique, and she was beautifully matched by Ethan Stiefel&#39;s Prince, nobly showing the true grand manner. Saturday afternoon had an ardent and gracious Angel Corella partnering a truly wondrous Paloma Herrera, who more than once suggested another Aurora with South American ethnic roots, the great Margot Fonteyn. Such performances - and a few other ones, such as Sascha Radetsky&#39;s controlled power as the Bluebird, also Sarah Lane as Princess Florine, and both Michele Wiles and Stella Abrera as the Lilac Fairy - suggest that, despite the tawdry new staging, individuals will continue to offer considerable pleasure and artistry. The dancers face an uphill struggle, and will certainly all achieve more by acting less. This is not meant to be 21st-century soap opera - it&#39;s 19th-century ballet. Metropolitan Opera House, Lincoln Center, Broadway at West 65th Street; (212) 362-6000. Season runs through July 7. NEW ABT&#39;S IS A SLEEPING UGLY ENTERTAINMENT HEADLINES FROM OUR PARTNERS NEW YORK POST is a registered trademark of NYP Holdings, Inc. NYPOST.COM, NYPOSTONLINE.COM, and NEWYORKPOST.COM are trademarks of NYP Holdings, Inc. Copyright 2007 NYP Holdings, Inc. All rights reserved.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/11i-0&fd=R&url=http://www.adotas.com/2007/06/nielsen-ratings-tell-all-how-wil-advertisers-bounce-back/&cid=1116772926&ei=h4BkRteEHIL0rQO9rMChBg Adotas &raquo; Nielsen Ratings Tell All. How Wil Advertisers Bounce Back? Skip to the main content Where media buyers start online Park Place, Boardwalk, FeedBurner&#8230;.Google Buys More Property Pay-Per-Click Pals Marchex Inc. and Yahoo! Team Up Literary World Finds New Audience Through Online Advertising YouTube Gets A Boost The Size Of EMI Rupert Murdoch One Step Closer To Owning Everything Nielsen Ratings Tell All. How Wil Advertisers Bounce Back? Last week Nielsen released its commercial rating data comfirming what has been speculated for some time now: that about 5% to 10% fewer people watch commercials than the show in which they appear. Networks are more interested in TiVo talk. The push will come for the upfront to include DVR viewers, hoping that a figure will come out that is at least around last year&#8217;s pfront take, estimated at $8.75 billion to $9 billion.u Even though reports show hat 97% of viewing occurs live, the tv networks still shift the focus to DVR users. Marketers expecting toÂ  discuss the large number of viewers lost during commercial breaks were surprised to be caught in the value of live viewers vs. DVR users debate. Until now, marketers have paid TV networks for ad time based on the popularity of shows, not viewership of the commercials themselves. Commercial ratings are going to change that, allowing prices to be set by viewership of ad breaks. While the new Nielsen ratings don&#8217;t track individual ads or specific time slots, they offer average viewership of all the national commercial minutes in a program. And that could be the blueprint upon which this year&#8217;s upfront deals are struck. Buyers and sellers seem to be coming to an agreement on &#8220;live plus three,&#8221; allowing the ratings to include viewers who watch as many as three days later. &#8220;It gives the media credit for the way in which people are and will increasingly watch TV, and that&#8217;s in some sort of time-shifted mode,&#8221; said Alan Wurtzel, president-research and media development for NBC Universal. The problem is that most viewers who can scroll past ads&#8230;.do. According to Nielsen, about 17% of U.S households have DVRs, and viewers 18 to 49 watch 10% of all broadcast-network prime-time programming via DVR. Network executives estimate more than half of those viewers skip the ads altogether. A number of big-spending categories are time sensitive. Package-goods marketers, for instance, often use TV ads to push products being promoted with coupons. If an ad tells people to &#8220;pick it up in this Sunday&#8217;s paper,&#8221; and the ad is viewed after Sunday, &#8220;that message has now been devalued,&#8221; said Scott Haugenes, senior VP-group director, national broadcast, Initiative. Fast-food marketers often have tie-ins to short-lived promotions &#8212; offers for particular sandwiches or film openings. Even though DVRs don&#8217;t account for the majority of viewers, &#8220;there will be more every single day,&#8221; said Ed Gold, director-corporate advertising for State Farm Insurance. &#8220;We are very concerned about utilizing any playback numbers until it&#8217;s proven to us that people actually watch the commercials during playback.&#8221; Still with commercial ratings being developed, the year&#8217;s upfront is anticipated to progress at a lethargic pace. Last.fm Paid $280 Million By CBS For Combining Musical Taste And Technology Shake-up at ValueClick, CEO Steps Down Microsoft Has Sour Grapes: Tattles on Google To Regulators FTC Puts Google/DoubleClick Deal Under The Microscope Exploring The Possibilities Of Contextual Ads For Online Video This is inevitable. However, commercial ratings could have an unintentional negative side effect. If shows are supported based on whether or not their viewers watch the commercial, we may end up with a bunch of boring shows geared at older, non-tech savvy people. Commercial ratings should ONLY be used to tell sponsors whether or not they produced a commercial the people actually want to watch. They should not be used to determine whether or not to sponsor a show. If you make a good and engaging commercial, people will watch it. In fact, they&#8217;ll You Tube it and blog it and tell their friends about it! | 1:16 pm on June 4, 2007. Nielsen Ratings Tell All. How Wil Advertisers Bounce Back? &raquo;Technology News | Venture Capital, Startups, Silicon Valley, Web 2.0 Tech Study Reveals Online Retail Sites Have More Impact With Video More than one in three Internet users would find their number one method of product research more impactful if accompanied [...] Nielsen Ratings Tell All. How Wil Advertisers Bounce Back? Last week Nielsen released its commercial rating data comfirming what [...] Park Place, Boardwalk, FeedBurner&#8230;.Google Buys More Property Google finally announced their long rumored acquisition of FeedBurner. FeedBurner is [...] Pay-Per-Click Pals Marchex Inc. and Yahoo! Team Up SEATTLE, WA, June 4, 2007 â Marchex, Inc. (Nasdaq: MCHX) [...] RealPlayer Moves Towards The Head Of The Class According to a RealNetworks news release, RealPlayer will have an [...] Literary World Finds New Audience Through Online Advertising Reuters has reported that many publishers are turning to social [...] YouTube Gets A Boost The Size Of EMI Today EMI Group and Google made an agreement that will [...] Rupert Murdoch One Step Closer To Owning Everything Rupert Murdoch has proven to be a true media mogul [...] Sour Taste Of Spam Brings Down Robert Alan Soloway Wednesday was not a good day for Robert Alan Soloway. [...] Growing Up: The Rise of Media Whiz - CEO Jonathan Shapiro Speaks Out ADOTAS editor and owner spent a few minutes getting to know Jonathan Shapiro, a man whose career has profoundly influenced [...] Nielsen Ratings