http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/19033979/&cid Will Paris learn her lesson? Letâs hope so - Celebrity Insights - MSNBC.com Will Paris learn her lesson? Letâs hope so Our columnist looks back on her encounters with the charming socialite Paris Hilton turned herself in to begin her three-week stint at the Century Regional Detention Facility. Hours after strolling the red carpet in a strapless black dress, Hilton traded her designer duds for a jail-issued jumpsuit. By By Miki Turner I donât know what pleases me most. The fact that The Rock is reportedly leaving his wife or that Paris Hilton is now behind bars. OK. Donât start clogging up my mailbox. Iâm really sorry that The Rockâs marriage is busting up. Thatâs not even funny. A girl, however, can dream about being his pebble mama canât she? But even though Iâm glad Hilton is now in the slammer and will hopefully engage in some R&R â redemption and reflection â thatâs really no laughing matter either. Hilton, 26, turned herself in late Sunday night just a few hours after attending the MTV Movie Awards where host Sarah Silverman made the hotel heiress the butt of numerous jokes. Prior to the show, Hilton told reporters on the red carpet that she was scared, but ready to serve her time. She also said that she hoped she could serve as âan example to other young people when they make decisions.â Thatâs one of those jokes you canât laugh at â particularly if she really believes that. The charms of Paris Iâve met Paris Hilton a few times. The first time was right before âThe Simple Lifeâ â the reality show starring Hilton and her BFF Nicole Richie â Â hit the air and became appointment TV. I had no idea who she was then but she seemed fairly harmless, standing alone behind a potted plant in a hotel corridor chomping on carrot sticks and celery. That night our paths crossed again at a Fox network party. Hilton and Richie crashed the mattress I was sharing with some friends of mine from 