uments before the U.S. appeals court panel in December 2006. In their written ruling on Monday, Judges Rosemary Pooler and Peter Hall said that the FCC policy on indecency standards "represents a significant departure from positions previously taken by the agency and relied on by the broadcast industry" and that the commission "has failed to articulate a reasoned basis for this change in policy." Judge Pierre Leval issued a dissenting opinion, writing that he believed the FCC "gave a reasoned explanation for its change of standard." ((Reporting by Martha Graybow, editing by Richard Chang; Reuters Messaging: martha.graybow.reuters.com@reuters.net; +1-646-223-6133)) Keywords: DECENCY COURT/ (C) Reuters 2007. All rights reserved. Republication or redistribution ofReuters content, including by caching, framing or similar means, is expresslyprohibited without the prior written consent of Reuters. Reuters and the Reuterssphere logo are registered trademarks and trademarks of the Reuters group ofcompanies around the world.nN04489269 &copy; Reuters 2007. All rights reserved. Editors Choice: Best pictures from the last 24 hours. UPDATE 1-Two ex-Putnam managers settle SEC trading charges START News Content Page Tags 'Text' | 'Picture' | 'Slideshow' | 'Video' ie. headline for article ie. headline for article END News Content Page Tags In quotes: Subprime fallout The stories behind the deals and the deal-makers as seen and heard by Reuters reporters covering mergers & acquisitions and Wall Street. Deals of the Day: Read the latest headlines Rounding up the papers Proxy firm backs Countrywide say-on-pay proposal US court rejects FCC broadcast decency rule UPDATE 1-Two ex-Putnam managers settle SEC trading charges Top Company Research Reports on Reuters.com Qantas Airways Ltd. [QAN] Globalstar IPO Update [GSAT] MFS Research Bond Fund [MRBFX] Reuters in Second Life Reuters is the world's largest international multimedia news agency, providing investing news, world news, business n