http://www.forbes.com/feeds/ap/2007/06/04/ap3783690.html&cid Paris Hilton Checks Into L.A. Jail - Forbes.com Paris Hilton Checks Into L.A. Jail 06.04.07, 6:45 AM ET Hours after strolling the red carpet in a strapless black dress, Paris Hilton traded her designer duds for a jail-issued jumpsuit. The 26-year-old heiress checked into the Century Regional Detention Facility in Lynwood just after 11:30 p.m. Sunday. She's expected to serve three-weeks for violating her probation in an alcohol-related reckless driving case. Hilton surrendered to sheriff's deputies after making a surprise visit to the MTV Movie Awards in the afternoon. "I am trying to be strong right now," she told reporters on the red carpet. "I'm ready to face my sentence. Even though this is a really hard time, I have my family, my friends and my fans to support me, and that's really helpful." Sheriff's spokesman Steve Whitmore said Hilton was easy to work with. "Her demeanor was helpful. She was focused, she was cooperative," he said. Hilton turned herself in at the Men's Central Jail in downtown Los Angeles just after 10:30 p.m., then was escorted to the all women's facility in Lynwood, where she was booked, fingerprinted and issued a jail uniform, Whitmore said. She also was given her first meal: cereal, bread and juice. So far, Hilton does not have a cellmate, Whitmore said. The "Simple Life" star will be housed in the "special needs" unit of the 13-year-old jail, separate from most of its 2,200 inmates. The unit contains 12 two-person cells reserved for police officers, public officials, celebrities and other high-profile inmates. Like other inmates in that unit, Hilton will take her meals in her cell and will be allowed outside the 12-foot-by-8-foot space for at least an hour each day to shower, watch TV in the day room, participate in outdoor recreation or talk on the telephone. No cell phones or BlackBerrys are permitted in the facility, even for visitors. The jail, a two-story concrete building next to train tracks and beneath a bustling freeway, has been an all-female facility since March 2006. It's located in an industrial area about five miles southeast of downtown Los Angeles. "I did have a choice to go to a pay jail," Hilton said Sunday, without giving details. "But I declined because I feel like the media portrays me in a way that I'm not and that's why I wanted to go to county, to show that I can do it and I'm going to be treated like everyone else. I'm going to do the time, I'm going to do it the right way." When she was sentenced May 4, Superior Court Judge Michael T. Sauer ruled that she would not be allowed any work release, furloughs or use of an alternative jail or electronic monitoring in lieu of jail. Sometimes stars are allowed to do their time in a jail of their choosing. In such cases they pay a daily room-and-board fee to the smaller jails, which afford them more privacy and comfort. Cop-slapping actress Zsa Zsa Gabor, for example, served three days behind bars in 1990 at the El Segundo jail near the Los Angeles International Airport. She paid $85 a day. On Saturday, about 15 photographers, reporters and television crews staked out the entrances to the jail waiting for the celebutante's arrival. Authorities had also cordoned off a grassy area outside the facility for the media. She had until Tuesday to report. On Sunday, about a dozen photographers and television crews were at the Lynwood facility when she arrived in an unmarked SUV. Video captured by celebrity news site TMZ.com showed Hilton inside the vehicle with her mother, Kathy. Hilton's publicist, Elliot Mintz, said he spoke with Kathy Hilton after she returned from the jail. "She told me it was very emotional," Mintz said. "She also said that she feels this will be a time when Paris will be able to think and reflect and to spend time alone to learn from the experience because in Paris' life she's never alone - there's always a constant chatter around her." Officers arrested Hilton in Hollywood on Sept. 7. In January, she pleaded no contest to the reckless-driving charge and was sentenced to 36 months' probation, alcohol education and $1,500 in fines. She was pulled over by California Highway Patrol on Jan. 15. Officers informed Hilton she was driving on a suspended license and she signed a document acknowledging she was not to drive. She then was pulled over by sheriff's deputies on Feb. 27, at which time she was charged with violating her probation. Associated Press Writer Peter Prengaman contributed to this report. Copyright 2007 Associated Press. All rights reserved. This material may not be published broadcast, rewritten, or redistributed More On This Topic ",">"); transformedStoryStr=transformedStoryStr.replaceAll(""","\""); out.write(transformedStoryStr); %--> Starting A Small Business Brought to you by the sponsors below A new book from brings the Himalaya experience home.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/19-2&fd=R&url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/artsentertainment/2003729548_broadway030.html&cid=1116883919&ei=h4BkRteEHIL0rQO9rMChBg Arts & Entertainment | Risk-taking musicals cut loose on Broadway | Seattle Times Newspaper Send us news tips Sunday, June 3, 2007 - Page updated at 02:01 AM Risk-taking musicals cut loose on Broadway Seattle Times theater critic JOAN MARCUS / AP "Spring Awakening," based on a play that shocked Europe at its 1891 premiere and featuring a punk-folk-rock score, has 11 Tony nominations, the most of any show in the 2006-07 season. JOAN MARCUS / AP Robin de Jesus, left, and writer-composer-star Lin-Manuel Miranda of "In the Heights," about the struggles and aspirations of Latino New Yorkers. Christine Ebersole, center, dazzles in double roles in "Grey Gardens," about eccentric relations of Jackie Kennedy Onassis. JOAN MARCUS / BARLOW-HARTMAN P.R. The energetic Laura Bell Bundy has the lead role in the slick but safe "Legally Blonde," based on the 2001 Reese Witherspoon film about an atypical Harvard Law coed. NEW YORK CITY &#8212; The short version of New York's most-promising new trend: Several refreshingly gutsy, nonformulaic musicals quietly sneaked into Broadway berths this season. And now they are raising a racket. "Spring Awakening" and "Grey Gardens" are musical dramas of substance and bite. And if their box-office prospects are iffy, the pair have stayed put long enough to rake in a lion's share of Tony Award nominations (the awards will be handed out next Sunday and broadcast by CBS), and cast a strong vote for more Broadway musicals that break the mold. Maybe it's not so surprising. The jukebox musical craze is cooling, as evidenced by Twyla Tharp's recent, short-lived "The Times They Are A-Changin'," a harshly panned tuner based on Bob Dylan songs. The British/French pop-opera invasion is having only a singular, tepid resurgence with "The Pirate Queen" (scored by "Miss Saigon" creators Alain Boublil and Claude-Michel Sch&#246;nberg). Sure, the craze for splashy new musicals geared toward youth and based on Hollywood movie comedies (the new "Legally Blonde") and Disney kid-flicks ("Tarzan," "Mary Poppins") is going strong. But "serious" new tuners on the Great White Way (like such admirable earlier exemplars as "Caroline, Or Change" and "The Light on the Piazza") may help carve out a permanent niche for admirable experimentation &#8212; and much-appreciated variety. The 61st Annual Tony Awards will be broadcast at 8 p.m. June 10 on KIRO-7. Read Misha Berson's Tony preview next Sunday. Here is a closer look at the upstarts &#8212; and a peek at a sign-of-the-times, crowd-pleasing Off Broadway attraction. Erotically charged and bitterly audacious, Frank Wedekind's play shocked Europe in its 1891 premiere for its daring study of sexual repression and hypocrisy in provincial Germany. The young lovers who couple and crash in Wedekind's script are resurrected in a combustible new musical, which has nabbed 11 Tony nominations, the most for any show in Broadway's 2006-07 season. The shock value of the graphic coming-of-age tale invented by Wedekind, and faithfully adapted for the stage by Steven Sater, has diminished. But the ill-fated romance of two ferociously sensitive, lusty (and sexually clueless) adolescents, Melchior (Jonathan Groff) and Wendla (Lea Michele), still resonates in a nation where sex education is a matter of fierce debate &#8212; and teen suicide and violence are persistent concerns. No question that the uptight parents and teachers who preach conformity and abstinence are the heavies in this spree of raw, unruly adolescent frustration. More individualized are the kids, played mostly by Broadway novices who tear up the stage in Michael Mayer's propulsive production. They stomp and stamp through the rousing choreography by the great Bill T. Jones. They sing out, strong and true, the compelling punk-folk-rock score, composed by singer-songwriter Duncan Sheik with lyrics by Sater. Mainstreaming alt-contemporary and Brechtian ensemble techniques that are increasingly common now on Broadway, "Spring Awakening" welds its gifted young crew into an inspired mass of angst. Individual characters pop into focus when they grab a mic, stare into the crowd and whoop out anguished rockers ("Bitch of Living"), searching soliloquies ("Mama Who Bore Me"), and intertwining duets ("The Guilty Ones"). Is "Spring Awakening" the new "Rent," as some suggest? There are certainly parallels, in spirit and form, between the two shows. But "Spring Awakening" has no instant standard in its score, like Rent's "Seasons of Love," and its rawness is a more radical departure from Broadway musical conventions. And in terms of pathos, "Rent," for me, was more affecting in its group portrait of young adult bohemians facing AIDS in lower Manhattan during the 1980s. "Spring Awakening" is edgier and more distancing but also (ironically) more contemporary, as it hooks into the eternal, hormone-driven whirlwind of puberty &#8212; which there will likely never be a cure for. This gets my vote for the weirdest, most subversive musical on Broadway, and the unlikeliest to land there. Doug Wright's book for the show, based on the lives of world-class eccentrics (and Jacqueline Onassis relations) Edith Bouvier Beale and her daughter "Little Edie," is sharply bifurcated. Act 1 presents a perverse twist on a Noel Cowardesque drawing-room romantic comedy, in which moneyed, colorful gentry sip champagne and swap witticisms in a country manse. Act 2 swerves into a grotesque fable, a kind of hybrid of "Mommy Dearest" and "Whatever Happened to Baby Jane?" set to music. What happened to Edith and Little Edie was documented in the cult documentary film "Grey Gardens," set amid the squalor this joined-at-the-hip pair were living in when the filmmaking brothers Albert and David Maysles turned their cameras on them. In a brilliant twofer performance, Christine Ebersole portrays both of the show's antiheroines in turn. She is a deceptively glossy, but truly unhinged Edith, the 1941 high-society wife threatened by the beauty and talent of daughter Edie (Erin Davie). And flashing forward to 1973, Ebersole eerily morphs into a pathetic yet strangely valiant middle-aged Edie &#8212; still in the clutches of Big Edie (played by the marvelous Mary Louise Wilson in Act 2) &#8212; and now mad as a hatter herself. The Scott Frankel-Michael Korie score is adept and lush in its use of past Broadway idioms. And Allen Moyer's dual scenic design, which displays the Beales' East Hampton fortunes from riches to ruin, is tops. But it is Ebersole's uncanny ability to turn us into both gawking voyeurs and caring confidants that makes the show so disturbing. In Little Edie's bizarrely dressed, fitfully hopeful and trapped state, we see just how warped the American Dream can get, and how low "high society" can plunge &#8212; Kennedy connection, or not. There is less to say about this frothy stage treatment of the hit Reese Witherspoon movie about a ditzy airhead who discovers she has a legal-eagle brain and a moral backbone while trying to prove herself to a boyfriend who is so not worth it. With serviceable songs by Laurence O'Keefe and Nell Benjamin; lots of perky dancing devised by director-choreographer Jerry Mitchell; and a likable-enough cast headed by the highly energetic Laura Bell Bundy, "Legally Blonde" is expertly put together and executed. It also is a feat of engineering over inspiration, and about as substantial as a cone of pink cotton candy. Accessorized with a lot of second-generation Valley Girl jokes, Gregg Barnes' witty costuming and a blaring message about tolerance and girl power, "Legally Blonde" is a high-end sports car compared to the messier, riskier new musical vehicles on Broadway. A great many parents will bring their pubescent girls to this show, rather than risk a more provocative, uncertain encounter with "Spring Awakening" or "Grey Gardens." No harm in that &#8212; but no adventure either. This ebullient outing by the generously gifted writer-composer-star Lin-Manuel Miranda brings something new and hot to Off Broadway. The title refers to Washington Heights &#8212; a largely Latino, upper Manhattan neighborhood. And a sense of that district's vibrant street life and ethnic pride radiates throughout Miranda's folksy musical about the challenges of Latino Americans trying to make their own life choices while honoring hard-working immigrant elders. The annals of New York theater are filled with such cross-generational sagas. What soars highest in "In the Heights" is its spunk, and its score laced with cogent, articulate rap numbers and zesty salsa tunes. Broadway has rarely embraced either rap or Latino music. But judging from the gusto and accessibility of Miranda's piquant show, and the raved-about new Off Broadway rap and rock musical "Passing Strange," maybe it's time. Copyright &#169; 2007 The Seattle Times Company More arts & entertainment headlines... Hiking accident, hit-and-run claim Inglemoor grads You may become medical guinea pig without knowing it Credit scorer aims to end "rental" of good ratings Motorcycle ridership grows; rider death rate grows faster Despite a warm day, M's Feierabend keeps cool for 1st win Obama and Edwards clash sharply on war in 2nd debate Light-rail debt a 50-year ride Gates grant for health institute is UW's largest Paris Hilton checks into L.A. jail for three-week stay Trucks losing tires leave State Patrol at a loss Lisa Francoise's quirky Ravenna store deals in spa and beauty products made with chocolate, including lip balm and body wash. The Seattle Times Company
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/14-3&fd=R&url=http://www.nytimes.com/2007/06/04/business/media/04nbc.html%3Fref%3Dbusiness&cid=1116962376&ei=h4BkRteEHIL0rQO9rMChBg NBC Names Program Executive to Head TV Studio - New York Times NBC Names Program Executive to Head TV Studio Sign In to E-Mail or Save This Published: June 4, 2007 NBC Universal took another step in revamping its television entertainment operations yesterday, appointing Katherine Pope as president of its television production studio, NBC Universal Television. The move came less than a week after it hired the independent producer Ben Silverman as a co-chairman, with Marc Graboff, of the television group, with authority over both the entertainment division of the NBC network and the television studio. That appointment, which coincided with the removal of Kevin Reilly as president of NBC Entertainment, raised questions about the future of Ms. Pope, who had been the top program development executive for NBC and was one of the most highly regarded young executives at the network. But NBC Universal acted quickly to answer those questions by giving Ms. Pope authority over the studio, which is producing hit shows like Heroes and The Office for NBC and House for Fox. Ms. Pope, who is in her mid-30s, will succeed Angela Bromstad, who headed the studio before she stepped away from the job several months ago. Ms. Bromstad is expected to be appointed to another NBC Universal position, perhaps heading its international division in London. Ms. Pope said in a telephone interview yesterday that she expected to hit the ground running in her new position, speaking to writers and producers and instigating new programs as quickly as possible. She said she has been impressed by Mr. Silvermans passion and vision. Hes like a hurricane of energy and ideas, she said. The studio will take risks both monetarily and creatively, Ms. Pope said. Asked what that might entail, she said she would encourage writers to bring new ideas and would give them latitude in carrying out those ideas. The studio hopes to commission pilots as early as this summer, she said. NBC continues to trail the other broadcast networks and needs hit programs. Ms Pope said she saw the studio as having two clients, the writers and NBC. Beyond the quest for a new generation of hits, Ms. Pope said she and Mr. Silverman had discussed the larger questions of where the business is going. That, she said, means thinking about new ideas, new avenues of distribution and the necessity to think globally about our content. Next Article in Business (17 of 20) &#x00bb; Need to know more? 50% off home delivery of The Times. To find reference information about the words used in this article, double-click on any word, phrase or name. A new window will open with a dictionary definition or encyclopedia entry. NBC, in Shake-Up, Names Outsider to a Top Position NBC Brings In Programming Help '60 Minutes' Creator Takes On Rockettes TV SPORTS; Network Shuffle Leaves N.H.L. Out in the Cold Next Article in Business (17 of 20) &#x00bb; Follow the Frugal Traveler on his 12-week cross-country journey See how the trip began What did he think of the Armuchee Bluegrass Festival? Tell him where to go in Tennessee and Kentucky Elizabeth Taylor - 1985 Media & Advertising &#x00bb; The Lede: Paris Hilton Reports to Prison Grey Gardens Provides the Role of a Life Home Fires: Iraq Veterans Return All of a Sudden, the Weather Is Controversial The New York Times Company
