http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/19-5&fd=R&url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/108515.html&cid=1116883919&ei=h4BkRteEHIL0rQO9rMChBg Playbill News: Sundance Lab Was Significant Fertilizer for Grey Gardens If you can see this, your browser does not support iframes! If you can see this, your browser does not support iframes! If you can see this, your browser does not support iframes! 16 May 2007 -- Ebersole's "Edies" Will Play London; U.S. Tour Also in the Works 09 May 2007 -- Ebersole and Maysles Talk About on Court TV's "Hollywood Heat" May 10 03 May 2007 -- Will Perform at Times Square Virgin Megastore May 10 03 Apr 2007 -- Ebersole on Vacation From 27 Mar 2007 -- Album Gets March 27 Web Release; Earlier Disc Goes for a Song Sundance Lab Was Significant Fertilizer for photo by Joan Marcus The road to Tony Awards success on Broadway has many developmental way stations  commissions, readings, workshops, concert presentations and more. Increasingly, the Sundance Institute Theatre Lab, based in Utah and sponsor of workshop retreats in Utah, Florida and Wyoming, is popping up as one of those important rest stops where new work is nurtured. Among past Broadway shows that have enjoyed Sundance development are 2004 Best Play Tony Award winner I Am My Own Wife and 2005 Best Musical nominee The Light in the Piazza. The 2007 Best Musical nominees both benefited from time with Sundance: was at the 2001 Sundance Institute Theatre Lab in Sundance, UT, and was at the 2005 Sundance Theatre Lab at White Oak in Yulee, FL. (A third Institute retreat, for playwrights, is held on the Ucross Foundation's ranch in Wyoming.) Michael Mayer, the Tony-nominated director of , said that "time" was the greatest gift that Sundance gave his project. He also appreciated that it was away from critics, away from New York and was all about process. The Sundance summer lab is in the Utah mountains, where artists can almost touch the sky. team learn at Sundance in balmy Florida? "Amazing things," said Tony-nominated director Michael Greif. "With the lab, we were able to cast a two-week workshop with most of the people who are still in the company, so Sundance and their casting directors had a lot to do with getting us here." The atmosphere at White Oak  a Florida plantation, again far from New York  was inspirational, Greif said. "The most amazing thing that happened at Sundance was that [2007 Tony Award nominees] Christine [Ebersole] and Mary Louise [Wilson] started inspiring [Tony-nominated composer] Scott [Frankel] and [Tony-nominated lyricist] Michael [Korie] to write amazing material," Greif explained. "Michael wrote the lyrics to 'Another Winter in a Summer Town' while we were at Sundance; Scott and Michael wrote 'Around the World' while we were at Sundance. 'Another Winter' was first performed as a poem. Christine it  it was truly extraordinary." It was at the Sundance White Oak Lab that Tony-nominated librettist Doug Wright "found a way to create a structure for the second act based on the musical material," Greif said. Act One of the musical is an imagined day in the life of the high society Beale Family in 1941 East Hampton, Long Island  very "Philip Barry," Greif said. Act Two borrows more from the "Grey Gardens" film documentary that inspired the musical. The vibrant mother and daughter of Act One are now dissipated, emotionally strained and living in the same mansion, but it's in shambles. Very "Samuel Beckett," Greif observed of Act Two. Greif explained, "Doug said to Scott and Michael, 'We know what the material is  what the documentary is  begin writing the stuff that inspires you.' And then Doug started finding a way in which we could travel through a day, a year, a lifetime in that [second] act, connecting those musical anchors." The entire show was not complete at Sundance, Greif said, but "in the time we were there, we actually read through and staged the first act and made some very significant changes to the first act." Philip Himberg is producing artistic director of the Sundance Institute Theatre Program. For more information about programs of Sundance Institute, visit www.sundance.org. Click Here to Buy Tickets to This Show Christine Ebersole and cast in the Sundance Lab workshop of Send questions and comments to the Copyright © 2007 Playbill, Inc. All Rights Reserved. Click Here to enter to win a trip to the 2007 Tony Awards - Compliments of Cadillac. Click Here to enter to win a trip to the 2007 Tony Awards - Compliments of Cadillac. Beauty and the Beast 110 in the Shade Don Juan in Chicago ALSO SAVE ON BROADWAY'S BEST The Year of Magical Thinking Top news stories from PlaybillArts.com: Glynebourne Opera's Plan to Erect Wind Turbine Upsets Neighbors Architects Selected for $100 Million Arts Center at University of Chicago Pittsburgh to Drop 'Amusement Tax' on Non-Profit Arts Groups for more classical music, opera, dance and jazz news and features. with light showers and clearing What is Playbill Weather? Schedule of Upcoming Broadway Shows Schedule of Upcoming Off-Broadway Shows Broadway Rush and Standing Room Only Policies Long Runs on Broadway Cumulative Broadway Grosses Through December 24, 2006 Tony Awards 2007: What would you like to see win Best Special Theatrical Event? Jay Johnson: The Two and Only Kiki & Herb Alive on Broadway If you can see this, your browser does not support iframes!
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/17-3&fd=R&url=http://cbs2chicago.com/topstories/local_story_155142025.html&cid=1116966251&ei=h4BkRteEHIL0rQO9rMChBg cbs2chicago.com - Mega Divorce Deal: $183 Million To Ex-Wife Chicago news, weather, sports, traffic and video from cbs2chicago.com: Mega Divorce Deal: $183 Million To Ex-Wife Jun 4, 2007 1:08 pm US/Central Mega Divorce Deal: $183 Million To Ex-Wife Maya Polsky Entitled To Half Of Ex-Husband's Fortune, Judge Rules It's In To Be Out: Openly Gay Celebrities In what could become the largest divorce settlement in Illinois history, a judge today awarded $183 million to the ex-wife of a local energy industry millionaire. Cook County Circuit Judge William Boyd upheld the award--which is half of industry magnate Michael Polsky's fortune--to his former wife of more than 30 years, Maya Polsky. Howard Rosenfeld , the attorney for Maya Polsky, said this is the largest divorce verdict in the history of Illinois and could be the largest in the country. Lawyers for Michael Polsky will likely appeal the decision. Michael Polsky, 57, is chief executive of Invenergy LLC. His 55-year-old wife was mostly a stay-at-home mother durring their 31-year marriage. In 2002, the couple separated. Maya filed for divorce the next year, citing irreconcilable differences. The couple emigrated from Russia in the mid-1970s. They settled in Chicago in the 1980s and Michael Polsky built his fortune after founding Inverergy in the early 1990s. Maya Polsky's attorneys contend she should be considered a full partner her ex-husband's success. State law provides judges with no clear rules on how to divide marital assets. Maya's lawyers argued that the length of the couple's marriage was the key factor. Michael's lawyers urged Boyd to consider each spouse's financial contribution to the marriage. (&copy; MMVII, CBS Broadcasting Inc. All Rights Reserved.) 2 Bank Robbery Suspects Due In Court Tank Johnson Suspended For 8 Games Mega Divorce Deal: $183 Million To Ex-Wife Son of Robbery Victim Says Justice Helps Healing Family of Joliet Murder Victim Holds Vigil Parent's Guide to TV Ratings CBS Television Stations Digital Media &copy; MMVII, CBS Broadcasting, Inc. All Rights Reserved.
