Cook County judge this morning awarded what could be the largest divorce verdict in U.S. history, ruling that energy industry magnate Michael Polsky must pay his wife, Maya Polsky, $184 million. Michael Polsky's lawyers had asked Judge William Boyd to reconsider his initial judgment last year and reduce the award. Instead, Boyd raised the amount that Maya Polsky, 55, will get in the divorce  from the original $176 million to $184 million, according to her attorney, Howard Rosenfeld. Rosenfeld said he knows of no other verdict this big in U.S. divorce courts. The couple was married for 31 years. The Polskys emigrated from Russia with nothing more than 30 years ago. Trained as an engineer, Michael Polsky made his fortune in the energy business. He now heads Invenergy LLC. As he built the business, his wife raised their children. They ultimately had homes in Chicago, Glencoe, Wisconsin and Colorado, while, in recent years, Maya Polsky also opened the Maya Polsky Gallery. The award amounts to about a 50/50 split of the couple's assets, Rosenfeld said. He said that was fair, no matter how much money that comes to. Michael Polsky's lawyer unsuccessfully argued otherwise. "She was not a driving force of the business," attorney Joseph Tighe said. "We don't think the judge's decision gives proper considerations to the contributions of a spouse in the development of the estate." Make Us Your Home Page © Copyright 2007 Sun-Times News Group |
