http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/10-0&fd=R&url=http://www.hecklerspray.com/rosie-odonnell-to-publish-her-furious-paranoid-memoirs/20068599.php&cid=1116931536&ei=h4BkRteEHIL0rQO9rMChBg Rosie O&#8217;Donnell To Publish Her Furious Paranoid Memoirs - Hecklerspray: Music, Movies, TV, Celebs, Games and Gossip Rosie O&#8217;Donnell To Publish Her Furious Paranoid Memoirs Rosie O&#8217;Donnell To Publish Her Furious Paranoid Memoirs June 4th, 2007 at 16:30 by Stuart Heritage By leaving a daytime TV show, Rosie O&#39;Donnell has never been more famous - so now is exactly the right time for Rosie O&#39;Donnell to publish her memoirs, allowing everyone to find out what really goes on inside that lovably indignant head of hers. Rosie O&#39;Donnell has promised at a national book convention that she&#39;ll be publishing what she calls a memoir of the last 12 months later in the year. Although no details of Rosie&#39;s memoirs - probably titled ARRGH! I HATE EVERYONE! - have been made clear, it seems obvious to us that the book will just be a printed version of Rosie O&#39;Donnell&#39;s blog, only without half as many piss-awful videos or rambling, barely-coherent movies of Rosie O&#39;Donnell half-heartedly mumbling along to songs. So not as fun, obviously. By anyone&#39;s standards, Rosie O&#39;Donnell has had a hell of a year. This time 12 months ago Rosie O&#39;Donnell was a washed-up former talkshow host, professional lesbian and world&#39;s most rubbish . But Rosie&#39;s life was transformed when she was invited to anchor , the daytime TV show where women get to screech a barrage of their botched viewpoint at other women who, outraged, would screech back. Rosie O&#39;Donnell was always more of a bellower than a screecher, and the people in charge of didn&#39;t like Rosie&#39;s blog , but aside from that she was a perfect fit for the show. She was in. From then on Rosie O&#39;Donnell was on a non-stop thrill-a-minute rollercoaster ride. During Rosie&#39;s tenure on she got to witness first hand what a dishevelled drunk Danny DeVito is weirdly angry man Alec Baldwin is - plus it&#39;s where she first had contact with future husband-to-be O&#39;Donnell and Trump pretended to hate each other and then had a great big protracted quarrel to try and deflect attention from their blossoming romance. But what will define Rosie O&#39;Donnell&#39;s legacy on will be her last few days. Originally Rosie was all set to leave at the end of the current season - but then a ferocious, cringeworthy on-air split-screen catfight between Rosie O&#39;Donnell and Elisabeth Hasselbeck put an end to that plan. After ten minutes of hearing a fundamentalist creationist with a voice like a rape alarm howling about how brilliant war is, Rosie had enough and . And now we&#39;ll all get to read about all that stuff we already knew about in the forthcoming Rosie O&#39;Donnell memoirs, as Speaking at a breakfast gathering at BookExpo America, the publishing industry&#39;s annual national convention, O&#39;Donnell said her long-delayed memoir on fame will not be "vindictive" or "mean-spirited," but will offer a candid look at her very public life, including her brief, battling stint on "The View." Notice that careful wording there. Rosie O&#39;Donnell only said she wouldn&#39;t be vindictive, which sure leaves a lot of room for homogeneous bombastic obnoxiousness - which is handy, since that does seem to be Rosie&#39;s default setting these days. And don&#39;t think for a second that the Rosie O&#39;Donnell memoirs will go unchallenged. Elisabeth Hasselbeck is also planning a counter-memoir giving her take on Rosie&#39;s time at - and it&#39;ll be published just as soon as scientists discover a font that&#39;s objectionably shrill enough. Rosie O&#39;Donnell Documenting &#39;Interesting Year&#39; - Rosie O&#8217;Donnell Vs Hasselbeck: Donald Trump Finally Wades In Rosie O&#8217;Donnell Strops Off The View Forever Rosie O&#8217;Donnell Thinks Donald Trump Is Crazy Obsessed Rosie O&#8217;Donnell Vs Donald Trump: Now With Added Walterzzzz&#8230; Now Rosie Steps Out Of &#8216;The View&#8217; Madonna Sides Up In The Rosie O&#8217;Donald Feud No More Blogging For Rosie O&#8217;Donnell Rosie O&#8217;Donnell Vs Some Other Woman In TV Screechfest This entry was posted on Monday, June 4th, 2007 4:30 pm and is filed under . You can follow any responses to this entry through the from your own site. Mail (will not be published) (required) You can use these tags: Get the 'spray by email Rosie O'Donnell To Publish Her Furious Paranoid Memoirs Awesome Or Off-Putting: Video Of Frankenstein-ish Two Headed Dog Pirates Of The Caribbean Inevitably Wins MTV Movie Award Stewart Copeland From The Police â âWeâre Shitâ Pirates Of The Caribbean 3 Still Weekend Box Office Top Dog Paris Hilton Simpers Off To Jail For A Few Weeks SLACKERJACK - Nanny Mania 'Sin City 2' Possibly Not Happening Hugh Grant Escapes Charges For Berserk Bean Attack Come And Join The Hecklerspray Facebook Group Bald Britney Spears' Loopy-Doo Hair Pulled From eBay Miss Universe: Everyone Hates Miss USA Lindsay Lohan Back In Rehab After Chuffwitted Arrest Crash Watch My Generation By The Zimmers Britney Spears Drops Clothes Roy Le Pre on Hugh Grant Escapes Charges For Berserk Bean Attack Click4Fansites &raquo; Blog Archive &raquo; &#8216;Sin City 2&#8242; Possibly Not Happening on 'Sin City 2' Possibly Not Happening Paris Hilton Simpers Off To Jail For A Few Weeks Australian Prime Minister Wants Big Brother Banned steph c (newcastle upon tyne, england) on Marilyn Manson Has Sex With A Girl Just For You About Us &#038; Press Ads that SUCK / badvertising Film Reviews / Previews I&#8217;m A Celebrity Get Me Out Of Here Betting Music Reviews / Previews Phil Spector Murder Trial Sequels That Aren&#8217;t As Good As The Ones We Would Write TV Reviews / Previews Victoria Beckham Pig Chasing Stories Z-listingtoport: news from the gutter Who Ate All The Pies
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/7-4&fd=R&url=http://www.star-ecentral.com/news/story.asp%3Ffile%3D/2007/6/4/music/17912587%26sec%3Dmusic&cid=1116768102&ei=h4BkRteEHIL0rQO9rMChBg The Star Online eCentral - Malaysia Entertainment e C e n t r a l > News & Features Monday June 4, 2007 Macca returns! Grammy Award-winning singer-songwriter and ex-Beatle, Sir Paul McCartney, has a new studio album, It is out in Malaysia today on his new label Hear Music/Universal. The first single, , will be released on McCartneys 65th birthday (June 18). Fans of McCartney can win this new CD by calling 03-76202206 between 6pm and 6.30pm today and asking for McCartneys Memory Almost Full album. The first 30 callers will get the album. Galaxie Blog Latest Posts Baked Beans Drama Ends Well For Hugh Adam Levine Is No 'Male Paris' Star Publications (Malaysia) Bhd
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/16-2&fd=R&url=http://www.newsday.com/entertainment/arts/ny-etbeauty5242467jun04,0,4484280.story%3Fcoll%3Dny-arts-headlines&cid=1116948888&ei=h4BkRteEHIL0rQO9rMChBg 'Beauty's' in the eye of three beholders - Newsday.com 'Beauty's' in the eye of three beholders "The Sleeping Beauty" may be a simple matter for you and me, but not for ballet. Since 1890, when Tchaikovsky and Marius Petipa, choreographer to the Tsar, bent the fairy tale to theatrical ends, it has stood in for the story of classical ballet itself. The good fairies of classicism are Reason, Harmony and Balance. These Enlightenment virtues protect ballet from the dangers of chaotic individualism. To revive the iconic work is to pick your way through a ghost-haunted forest in ballet history. The choreographer must decide which shades to listen to and which to ignore as he fashions a "Sleeping Beauty" for today. The task is daunting. American Ballet Theatre's artistic director Kevin McKenzie has wisely chosen to share his choreographic duties, bringing on onetime prima ballerina Gelsey Kirkland and theater director Michael Chernov. As you'd expect when three smart people are all in charge, this "Sleeping Beauty" is at once visionary and not quite finished, with technical details to clean up. Still it's wonderful and rare to be offered such a vision - stretching from one end of the three-hour ballet to the other and accumulating force through imaginative detail. ABT's "The Sleeping Beauty" tells its story clearly, wisely and with an infectious delight in old-fashioned stage machinery. It also celebrates the origins of ballet - less in the French court of King Louis XIV than in the fairyland of the unconscious. The fairies prevail in the prologue, set in the king's palace, and in the dream scene - the heart of this version - when Princess Aurora meets Prince Desir&#233; in her sleep and charges him with the vigor to fend off the evil fairy, Carabosse, and rescue her from eternal slumber. In the wedding scene, the couple emerges from the subterranean world of hope and fear to join a pantheon of fairy-tale characters, stepping straight from feeling into art and skipping the world altogether, as dance often does. It's nothing new to have "The Sleeping Beauty" move from the court to the realm of fairies and legend: Tchaikovsky's vivid and allusive music invites these shifts. But McKenzie and team have woven a web of meaning that promises to deepen the magic. For example, they have reinstated the melancholy violin solo, unceremoniously cut a week before the 1890 opening, to flesh out our prince's budding feelings; at the first chords of the next violin solo, when the Lilac Fairy presents Desir&#233; with a vision of Aurora, you tingle with d&#233;j ... vu. The prince's steps suffer from the usual problem of moody solos: without anyone to react to, you can only express vague yearning. Perhaps a visit by the prologue's fairies is in order. The prince might adapt their gloriously eccentric steps to his own heroic and romantic purposes. And when he falls asleep and is whisked through the air by four fairy knights (this is ABT, where the boys do everything!), the whirl of dream is not yet whirly enough. He looks like Superman. Also inspired and riddled with small glitches is the imagery tied to Carabosse's deadly spindle: the maypole dance that a gaggle of innocent teenagers creates from its blood-red threads before they're caught out and threatened with death; a weaving and hooking ensemble dance with flower garlands that's worthy of Busby Berkeley; and Carabosse's metamorphosis into a spider. On Friday, the maypole number ended in a tangle and the spider scene took too long to establish its intoxicating mood, but these are fixable problems. As for the dancing, a case of nerves plagued opening night. Once the elegant Veronika Part failed to get off the ground for Aurora's famous toe hops, she fell into a daze and let the music wash over her like a ship in a storm. Marcelo Gomes was a noble prince, but not as emotionally textured as he can be. Michelle Wiles seemed weighed down by the burden of being chief fairy. Only former ballerina Martine Van Hamel seemed to be having any fun. As an Elizabeth Taylor of an evil fairy, she was thoroughly self-possessed, taking her good time to ruin the party. By the wedding, everyone had relaxed. A plucky Xiomara Reyes as Princess Florine endeared, and Herman Cornejo dazzled as the bluebird. . Choreography by Kevin McKenzie, Gelsey Kirkland and Michael Chernov after Marius Petipa. Through June 9 at the Metropolitan Opera House. The American Ballet Theatre spring season continues through July 7. Tickets $24-168. Call 212-362-6000 or visit abt.org. Seen Friday. Subscribe to Newsday home delivery Article licensing and reprint options Post a comment |
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/15-2&fd=R&url=http://www.kansas.com/entertainment/story/86118.html&cid=1116954934&ei=h4BkRteEHIL0rQO9rMChBg Kansas.com | 06/03/2007 | A man for 20 seasons Sign in to your Classified Account Buy Photos & Pages Open Road Motorcycle Edition From House to Home Posted on Sun, Jun. 03, 2007 A man for 20 seasons Wayne Bryan's 20th season at Music Theatre of Wichita includes four Wichita premieres and one beloved gem. Special to The Eagle When New York-based actor and director Wayne Bryan came to Wichita in 1986 as a guest artist for two shows with Music Theatre, he enjoyed himself but thought that was pretty much it. "I was brought in to direct 'Oklahoma!' and to be in 'Where's Charley?,' then went back to New York," Bryan recalled. "I thought that would be my Wichita experience because I was really very happy as a New Yorker. I was making a good living in theater and television and had been on Broadway." But Wichita wasn't quite done with Bryan. Music Theatre's then-producing director John Holly accepted a similar job in Houston and recommended that Bryan be considered as his successor. "I thought I might go for one summer to see what it was like. I began officially on April Fools' Day in 1988 and thought that would make a good story to tell my friends later," Bryan said with a laugh. But he's now beginning his 20th season as producing director of Music Theatre of Wichita and will have produced his 100th musical with the premiere of "Hairspray" in August. He's only the third person to lead Wichita's premier theatrical group, after founder Jim Miller and Holly. But he's the longest-running chief, heading up 20 of the group's 36 years and turning the theater from popular local summer entertainment into a nationally and internationally respected arts entity. Four years ago, his parents moved to Wichita from his original California hometown near Los Angeles to retire and be near him. "I guess I'm really here," he said. Bryan, who still has two windows of opportunity each year to guest-direct and guest-perform with other theater groups around the country, said he counts three milestones that have put Music Theatre in the big leagues. The first happened in 1993 when Bryan sought permission to rework the old college musical "Good News," which he had performed in on Broadway. "The authors were very reluctant to let us, but it had sat unproduced for years," he said. "We created a new libretto and new arrangements and made it into a really fun show. San Diego picked up our version, and it's now been done more than 250 times around the U.S., Canada and Great Britain. "Each time it's done, they have to give Music Theatre of Wichita credit in their programs. And the London cast went on to record a cast album, also giving us credit. We essentially revived a moribund show." The second milestone occurred in 2001, when Music Theatre presented the new musical "Honk!," a fanciful retelling of the fairy tale "The Ugly Duckling." It also recorded the first complete cast album, which has been shipped all over the world. "When you go to stores or Amazon.com, ours is the version you get," Bryan said. The third milestone came in 2004, when Bryan persuaded Disney to give Music Theatre a rare chance to stage its own "Beauty and the Beast," complete with new sets and costumes. Cautious Disney representatives who came to observe the show were so impressed that it opened doors for shots at other Disney shows, notably "Aida" in 2005 and the pre-Broadway tryout of "Disney's High School Musical," which opens the 2007 season next week. "Beauty and the Beast" also caused Music Theatre's costume and scenery shops to take a quantum leap in the minds of much older and larger theater groups, such as Philadelphia and Atlanta, who rented Wichita's trappings for their own productions. "Those sets and costumes have been on the road continuously for more than two years," Bryan said. "They've more than paid for themselves and now generate income for the theater. They've been back to be refurbished and are about to go out again. Our reputation has really grown beyond just being a theater that's a nice place to work in the summer." What keeps Bryan in Wichita is the artistic challenge and the community support he doesn't find in theaters elsewhere. "I find it fascinating that Wichita can support musical theater at the Broadway level while mounting its own shows," he said. "There's nothing like it in San Francisco or Chicago or Los Angeles these days. The touring shows have taken over their local productions." Music Theatre of Wichita can rise to the challenge because it's considered an educational troupe that uses a mix of Equity talent and college apprentices, both on stage and back stage. Bryan says the theater doesn't have to rely on bringing in celebrity names to sell a show. Instead, it's known as a training ground for young performers, who compete for the 25 or 26 slots in the repertory company and then occasionally are tapped to do larger roles. "They are at the age where they are so ready for the challenge," Bryan said. "Many times, when they have moved on to Broadway careers of their own, they come back as leads to pass on their experiences to the next generation." Michael Gruber, for example, took a two-week vacation from Broadway's "Miss Saigon" to perform "Singin' in the Rain" here. Gary Kilmer stepped out of his performance in Broadway's "Chicago" to direct Music Theatre's version in 2003. And last summer, Megan Osterhaus left Broadway's "Mamma Mia!" to cavort as "Thoroughly Modern Millie" here. She has since returned to Broadway in Disney's new "Mary Poppins." About the Real Cities Network About the McClatchy Company
