http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/6i-0&fd=R&url=http://northwestcountyjournal.stltoday.com/entertainment/sj2tn20070601-0601flo_knock.ii1.txt&cid=1116968833&ei=h4BkRteEHIL0rQO9rMChBg Northwest County Journal - Entertainment Select a Suburban Journal St. Clair County Journal Scott Air Force Base Katherine Heigl and Seth Rogen in a scene from "Knocked Up," a Universal Pictures release. 'Knocked Up' delivers laughs By L. Kent Wolgamott Monday, June 4, 2007 10:20 AM CDT Socially inept stoner meets hot television babe in a club. They drunkenly tumble into bed. She's appalled in the morning. A few weeks later, she discovers she's pregnant. That unlikely scenario is the basis of "Knocked Up," this summer's R-rated comedy from writer-director Judd Apatow, the man behind "The 40 Year-Old Virgin." A take-off of sorts from that picture, "Knocked Up" stars Katherine Heigl of ABC's "Grey's Anatomy" as Alison Scott, an E! network producer who finally gets her shot in front of the camera. Celebrating her promotion, she goes out clubbing with her married sister Debbie (Leslie Mann) and is rescued from an uncomfortable encounter by Ben Stone (Seth Rogen, who played Cal in "Virgin.") Layabout stoner Ben and his equally worthless friends see themselves as Internet entrepreneuers. But they're actually putting together a site that provides details on nudity in movies and have failed to check out the competition that's already on the Web. The picture's pivotal moments come when Alison tells Ben that she's expecting and he instantly decides he's going to stick around and be a dad. His choice is more than a little surprising and it sets off one of the many streams of humor that pour from the screen. To say that Ben has to go through a maturing process is an understatement. And he can't even turn to his dad (Harold Ramis) for help. Meanwhile, Alison is grappling with issues of her own, trying to hide her pregnancy from E! execs while becoming ever more confused because she's actually finding hairy schlub Ben to be kind of appealing. That's much of the charm of the very funny "Knocked Up." As deftly played by Rogen, Ben is a nice, if, shall we say, less than motivated guy who begins to find his niche while others remain appalled by him and his behavior. Apatow keeps things loose throughout. It's obvious that much of the film's fast-flying dialogue is improvised as the director trusts his cast, many of whom he's worked with in the past, to be funny while telling the story. There are subplots galore as well. Each of Ben's roommates/partners gets a little story as do Debbie and her husband Pete (Paul Rudd), who she suspects of having an affair. All those stories contribute to the film's two-hour-plus running time. Given that it's basically a romantic comedy with a predictable story arc, "Knocked Up" could have been trimmed significantly without doing much damage to its central story. But that kind of editing would have drastically cut down on the laughs, which start early and continue through most of the movie. That's a sharp contrast to most romantic comedies, which start out funny and wind up stuck in the mush. As was the case with "The 40 Year-Old Virgin" and "Wedding Crashers," "Knocked Up" benefits from its R rating. This is an adult comedy with adult themes that would have been blanded to the usual level of boredom had Apatow shot for the PG-13 that most filmmakers covet in order to gain the widest possible audience. To its credit, "Knocked Up" doesn't make any attempts at delivering any kind of social/cultural/political message. It's just a funny movie about a mismatched couple brought together by an accidental pregnancy - with the emphasis on funny. "Knocked Up" is rated R for sexual content, drug use and language. L. Kent Wolgamott is a movie critic with the Lincoln Journal Star WRITE LETTER TO EDITOR Write in your Journal! Your Journal encourages you to share thoughts on the preceding article. Comments are not posted to the site immediat