http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/7-6&fd=R&url=http://www.amny.com/entertainment/ny-etledew5242345jun05,0,3235548.story%3Fcoll%3Dam-ent-headlines&cid=1116768102&ei=h4BkRteEHIL0rQO9rMChBg Starbucks sweetener: A new McCartney CD - AM New York Mon, Jun 4, 2007 | 5:17 PM New York City Guide New York City Living Guide to Central Park Guide to Prospect Park Letters to the Editor Tell us: Best Promoters Starbucks sweetener: A new McCartney CD There's a lot of noise surrounding Paul McCartney's new album "Memory Almost Full." It's his first for Starbucks' new record label Hear Music, another sign of the deterioration of the major-label system. It's the 64-year-old's first album available for digital download, another sign of the growing strength of Internet distribution. It's also his first album since his messy breakup from his wife, Heather Mills, but those looking for clues about that will be sorely disappointed, since the album was written before their relationship-troubles began. In the end, though, none of that really matters. What does matter is "End of the End," an elegant, poignant new ballad about death that stands among the best of his solo career. "On the day that I die I'd like bells to be rung and songs that were sung to be hung out like blankets that lovers have played on and laid on while listening to songs that were sung," McCartney sings in his sweetest voice atop a beautiful piano melody, while building a case for the afterlife. It's the most direct song in this series about looking back over his life, which also includes the rocking single "Ever Present Past" and the wistful "Vintage Clothes" and "That Was Me." And it makes "Memory Almost Full" - which isn't as strong as 2005's excellent "Chaos and Creation in the Backyard" (Capitol), but still one of his most consistent albums in years - a worthy addition to his historically impressive catalog. . Paul McCartney looks back and moves forward. In stores today. Grade: B+. Though she's only 19 years old, Rihanna is a hitmaker from the old school, when teams of songwriters and producers pulled together to roll out hot singles and new albums with assembly-line precision. And on "Good Girl Gone Bad" (Def Jam), the Barbados native's third album release in less than two years, she finds her groove. Whether it's the epic-sounding, feel-good hip-hop of "Umbrella" with Jay-Z or the playful, edgy pop of "Breakin' Dishes" or the sweet, "Irreplaceable"-ish duet with Ne-Yo, "Hate That I Love You," Rihanna makes them all work with her pretty little voice and lighthearted vocal delivery. She must have learned her lesson from last year's uneven "A Girl Like Me" album and sidestepped all the sappy ballads in favor of upbeat dance numbers, mid-tempo ballads and island-tinged winners such as "Lemme Get That" and "Sell Me Candy." That makes "Good Girl Gone Bad" an album that is easy to listen to without being easy-listening bland, one of those rare pop collections where every song is a potential hit. ("Good Girl Gone Bad," in stores today; Grade: B+) . Chris Cornell goes solo on "Carry On" (Interscope/Suretone) with rock ranging from the Bond movie theme "You Know My Name" to a dirge-like, yowling cover of "Billie Jean"; Dream Theater's "Systematic Chaos" (Roadrunner); Bruce Springsteen and The Sessions Band capture the Pete Seeger tour on "Live in Dublin" (Columbia); O.A.R. captures its most recent tour on "Live from Madison Square Garden" (Atlantic); Country's hottest duo Big & Rich return with "Between Raising Hell and Amazing Grace" (Warner Bros.); Marilyn Manson's less-shock, more-rock "Eat Me, Drink Me" (Nothing/Interscope); Daddy Yankee's "El Cartel: The Big Boss" (Interscope); Poison's covers album "Poison'd" (Capitol); a tribute album to June Carter Cash "Anchored in Love" (Dualtone), including Elvis Costello doing "Ring of Fire"; a tribute album to Ella Fitzgerald "We All Love Ella: Celebrating the First Lady of Song" (Verve), including Queen Latifah doing "The Lady Is a Tramp"; and, at long last, the Afghan Whigs' greatest hits album "Unbreakable: A Retrospective 1990-2006" (Rhino), including two new songs from the underappreciated indie-rock masters. SONG(S) OF THE WEEK . Lil Mama is already building a teen audience with her hip-hop-cheerleader ode to that makeup staple "Lip Gloss" (Jive), which could grow into this summer's "Hollaback Girl." But the 17-year-old rapper from East New York is set to make her name with a pair of high-profile remixes. Her rhymes on the remix of Avril Lavigne's "Girlfriend" (RCA) cuts the shrieky quotient and raises the hip factor by turning Lavigne into simply the hook singer. On the remix of Rihanna's "Umbrella" (Def Jam), she replaces Jay-Z and manages to hold her own - a sure sign Lil Mama is gonna be something big. Post a comment | New York auto show New York International Auto Show Denise Flaim's Animal House blog Our up-to-the-minute subway blog, Tracker. Great photos - from NYC happenings to celebrities. See photos of the day Ultimate guide to having fun in New York City. New York City Guide NYC Subway & Bus Directions Check out the Fall 2007 designs New York City Restaurants Find restaurants in NYC. Top New York City hotels Bargain to deluxe, find a New York City hotel Watch videos, see photos of the People's Park Click any link to play that video or check boxes and click play. Battle for top dog heats up Death colors final 'Sopranos' hour Diner's video shows JFK plot suspect Winning design for Gateway Park unveiled Hilton Completes First Night in LA Jail Battle for top dog heats up What about the boys at Shea? Thousands pose nude in Amsterdam for artist Get your body to shine for summer NYPD focuses on weak spots By visiting this site, you are agreeing to our Copyright 2007 AM New York
