aravello not only alleges lack of payment and severe pain, but he also claims in the suit that he was humiliated when footage of the incident appeared on the internet. It's unclear if Caravello wasn't informed that the footage would be posted, didn't know he was being taped, or simply wasn't informed and felt abused when the footage appeared. , Jimmy Kimmel, and Adam Corolla all have yet to comment on the situation. Perry Caravello claims that he was to be paid by Jimmy Kimmel for his work on the 2003 film Windy City Heat and that promised payment if he promoted the film's DVD release on Adam Corolla's radio show. That's where the genitals of Mr. Caravello met the mousetrap. In the papers filed by the Los Angeles Superior Court, Caravello claims that he " agreed to do so and, much to his emotional tranquility and to his physical harm, was severely injured when the trap literally went on his manhood. " The legal action also mentions that he never gave permission to be filmed and was never paid for or given an account of the profits and royalties from DVD sales of the film, something he apparently was due for promoting in such a horrific manner. is most well-known for his work on MTV's Jackass and the two movies that followed but he also appeared in Coyote Ugly, Big Trouble, Men in Black II, Walking Tall, A Dirty Shame, Lords of Dogtown, The Dukes of Hazzard, and The Ringer. You can next catch in Killshot with Diane Lane, Mickey Rourke, Thomas Jane, Rosario Dawson, and Joseph Gordon-Levitt. Search our database of Celebrity Galleries: View our entire list of Celebrities Latino pride of Longoria's parents Paris Hilton checks into jail two days early Steamy Knightley scene shelved Anderson's phonecall to her heart Jolie and Pitt struggle with parenthood Court rejects FCC crackdown on TV networks Dead Man's Chest and Borat steal MTV Movie Awards Pirates of the Caribbean crosses $400 million Pirates holds top spot but Knocked Up really delivers Jeremy Sisto joins the cast 