http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/4-6&fd=R&url=http://www.wral.com/business/local_tech_wire/venture/story/1467515/&cid=1116959420&ei=h4BkRteEHIL0rQO9rMChBg New Atlanta-linked Game Company Launches with $400M :: WRAL.com WRAL.com - coverage you can count on | Raleigh * Durham * Fayetteville New Atlanta-linked Game Company Launches with $400M Posted: Today at 12:36 p.m. Brash Entertainment, a startup led in part by executives from Atlanta, is launching a videogame company with a whopping $400 million in financing. Backers include ABRY Partners, New York Life Capital Partners III, and Northwestern Mutual Life Insurance. The company promises a &ldquo;new business model for bringing licensed games to market.&rdquo; The firm will be based in Atlanta and Los Angeles. It already is working on several titles. Bert Ellis, an executive with the firm, is a former chief executive officer of iXL Enterprises, a defunct Web consulting firm in Atlanta. He also is an investor in Brash Music, a record label based in Atlanta, according to the Atlanta Business Chronicle. In March, the newspaper reported the company would get started with $150 million in funding. Mike McQuary, a former executive with Internet Service Provider EarthLink, is an investor in the firm. Brash&rsquo;s strategy calls for projects to be matched with independent development studios, the company said. Twelve games are already in production, and more than 40 properties have been licensed in deals with five film studios. "Brash is founded on the simple premise that top Hollywood creativity plus top game talent should equal great games," said Brash co-founder, Chairman, and CEO Mitch Davis in a statement. "We are laser focused on delivering high-quality games. The other aspects of our business are left to the experts - best of breed partners we've tapped for their specific expertise." Warner Bros. Home Entertainment Group is the distributor for Brash titles. Davis and Nicholas Longano, the chief operating officer, were former executives at Massive Incorporated, which developed an in-game advertising network. Copyright 2007 by WRAL.com. All rights reserved. This material may not be published, broadcast, rewritten or redistributed. Composite Sketches Released in Convenience Store Slaying Posted at 2:54 p.m. Driver Charged With DWI in Fatal I-40 Wreck Updated 40 minutes ago Woman Pleads Guilty to Fatal Hit-and-Run Updated 23 minutes ago 1 Wounded in Waffle House Shooting Updated at 7:45 a.m. Weekend Rain Helped, But Much More Needed to Ease Drought Updated at 10:44 a.m. Informant Helped Bust Alleged JFK Plot Updated at 11:59 a.m. Parents of TB Patient Are &#039;In Hell&#039; Updated 33 minutes ago Women Prosecuted for Smuggling Children Updated 43 minutes ago Dallas Could Elect Its First Gay Mayor Posted 31 minutes ago Court Backs Missouri Death Penalty Procedure Updated at 3:52 p.m. Woman Pleads Guilty to Fatal Hit-and-Run Composite Sketches Released in Convenience Store Slaying Teen Wanted in Slaying Surrenders 3 Arrested, $2 Million in Marijuana Seized Bush Heads to Europe for G-8 Summit Capitol Broadcasting Company, Inc.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/6-6&fd=R&url=http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news%3Fpid%3D20601088%26sid%3DaE67rOr2mMUU%26refer%3Dmuse&cid=1116968833&ei=h4BkRteEHIL0rQO9rMChBg , Jun 04 17:17 , Jun 04 22:17 , Jun 05 06:17 `Knocked Up&#39; Delivers Laughs, Lap Dances, Romance: Rick Warner June 4 (Bloomberg) -- Judd Apatow has followed up his surprise hit, ``The 40-Year-Old Virgin,&#39;&#39; with another ingratiating romantic comedy that might have been called ``The 23-Year-Old Accidental Dad.&#39;&#39; The real title, ``Knocked Up,&#39;&#39; is a punchier summary of this gender-divide film about the aftermath of a one-night stand between an ambitious, gorgeous blonde named Alison and Ben, a slovenly slacker. Like ``The 40-Year-Old-Virgin,&#39;&#39; it successfully mixes raunchy humor and juvenile antics with tender touches and adult conflicts. Writer/director Apatow gives us jokes about masturbation and buying condoms from Costco, yet we also get sweet moments such as the one where penniless Ben (Seth Rogan) gets down on his knee and proposes to Alison (Katherine Heigl) with an empty ring case. You&#39;d expect the mood shifts to be more jolting than they are; Apatow has a knack for melding the light and the serious, and treating them with equal respect. Ben and Alison meet at a Southern California bar where she&#39;s celebrating her promotion to on-air reporter at an entertainment-news network and he&#39;s hanging out with his stoner buddies, who are helping him create an Internet movie guide to nude scenes featuring famous actresses. Alison and Ben get drunk, fall into bed and presto, eight weeks later she discovers she&#39;s pregnant. (She apparently was so wasted she didn&#39;t realize he failed to use a condom.) When Alison decides to have the baby -- the choice seems implausible, given that she just met Ben and they&#39;re complete opposites -- Ben nonchalantly tells her that he&#39;s ``on board&#39;&#39; without having a clue what he&#39;s getting into. And so begins their rocky road to parenthood. While they both have serious reservations about a permanent relationship, Alison and Ben prepare for their impending arrival by shopping for baby books and cribs, as well as a trusted gynecologist -- the latter search taking forever because of Alison&#39;s determination to bond with her doctor. Meanwhile, Ben is bonding with his possible future brother- in-law, Pete (Paul Rudd), a fun-loving, henpecked father of two suspected of cheating by his wife, Debbie (Leslie Mann). Debbie follows her husband to a strange house one night, only to discover that he&#39;s innocently participating in a fantasy- baseball draft with his friends. To escape his wife&#39;s scrutiny, Pete heads to Las Vegas with Ben, where they hire lap dancers and hallucinate on psychedelic mushrooms. Ben returns in time to attend Alison&#39;s drug-free delivery, which comes with so much screaming and cursing that it might serve as an effective method of population control. Though I&#39;m skeptical that a couple like this would last longer than a Madonna hairdo, that didn&#39;t spoil my enjoyment of what is, after all, a Hollywood confection. Apatow&#39;s sharp script and a wonderful ensemble cast make ``Knocked Up&#39;&#39; a knockout. ``Knocked Up,&#39;&#39; from Universal Pictures, is playing across the U.S. (Rick Warner is the movie critic for Bloomberg News. The opinions expressed are his own.) To contact the writer of this story: Rick Warner in New York at Last Updated: June 4, 2007 00:11 EDT Bernstein Plays Amateur Freud, Cites Unnamed Sources in Craven Hillary Bio One-Eyed Taliban Leader, Group&#39;s Resurgence Probed on TV: Dave Shiflett New `Sleeping Beauty&#39; Shows off Great Aurora, Ghastly Decor: Tobi Tobias
