http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-spector5jun05,0,4101204.story%3Fcoll%3Dla-home-local&cid Spector's lawyers lose bid to use Clarkson's own words - Los Angeles Times 2:18 PM PDT, June 4, 2007 Buy, Sell & More Deals at Local Stores California | Local News Spector's lawyers lose bid to use Clarkson's own words The judge rejects an effort by the defense to use writings from the dead actress in the cross-examination of a medical examiner. By Michael Muskal, Times Staff Writer 12:54 PM PDT, June 4, 2007 The judge in the Phil Spector murder trial rejected efforts today by the defense to use parts of the apparent diary of Lana Clarkson in the cross-examination of the medical examiner who did an autopsy on the dead actress. Los Angeles County Superior Court Judge Larry Paul Fidler said he would not allow the computer document to be used in questioning Deputy Medical Examiner Louis Pena, who returned this morning for a fourth day on the stand. Pena, whose time in the witness box will resume this afternoon, insisted that he stood by his ruling that the death was a homicide. Today's ruling by Fidler was a surprise and a blow to the defense, which had hoped to use the document to undermine Pena and to raise questions about Clarkson's lifestyle. Fidler said the defense could try to introduce the document when it presented its case. Spector, 67, is accused of shooting Clarkson, 40, about 5 a.m. on Feb. 3, 2003, after the music producer spent the night drinking at several restaurants and clubs. Spector met Clarkson a few hours earlier at the House of Blues in West Hollywood, where the actress worked as a hostess for the Foundation Room, the club's VIP area. Fidler's decision was a surprise because he had indicated last week that he was inclined to allow the defense to introduce the document, titled "The Story of My Life." It was found on the hard drive of Clarkson's computer. The defense calls the document Clarkson's diary, a term to which the prosecution has objected. Fidler said he read the document over the weekend. He said it seemed dated, describing events in 1988 or 1989. He asked defense lawyer Christopher J. Plourd what bearing the material could have on Clarkson's death in 2003. "I don't consider anything in this particular document to be significant," Fidler said after the prosecution was unable to answer his questions. "If your experts want to" discuss the document "that's fine. The question was whether Dr. Pena could be cross-examined on this, and I find this to be so irrelevant that the answer is no," Fidler ruled. "You're not going to present it through him, because we'll wait and see if it ever gets presented at all. I find nothing of any probative value whatsoever in this item." Plourd argued the document indicated Clarkson's state of mind, and that the material seemed to jump around in time and could indicate more recent attitudes. He said computer experts say the document was worked on 2001. The ruling was a setback for Spector's defense team, which maintains that Clarkson accidentally shot herself because she was despondent about the decline of her performing career. The defense has called the death an "accidental suicide." But the defense faced a tactical problem in how to introduce evidence to support its contention without attacking Clarkson. By using the cross-examination of a prosecution witness, the defense had hoped to make its points without being in the uncomfortable position of attacking the victim. The document also would have given the defense ammunition to undermine Pena, who rejected the suicide theory when he testified last week and through three days of detail-laden cross-examination by the defense. Pena said he considered the possibility of suicide but decided that Clarkson was a victim of a homicide, in part because there was no evidence that she had been despondent. It also made no sense that Clarkson would go to a stranger's home and somehow find a gun to kill herself, Pena said. Plourd had argued that the computer document showed that Clarkson was despondent about her declining acting career and that she used alcohol and illegal drugs. She was also fascinated by guns, Plourd said. During his cross-examination, Plourd tried to get Pena to change his mind about his homicide ruling, but the coroner stood firm as the lengthy cross-examination ended in the late morning. Deputy Dist. Atty. Alan Jackson then took over the questioning and walked Pena through the various e-mails cited by the defense. Jackson read the full messages, trying to show that the defense's interpretation that Clarkson was suicidal was wrong. "Is there any suicidal ideation?" Jackson asked Pena. "No," the coroner replied. After Jackson finishes with Pena, the defense will get another chance to shake the medical examiner. Times staff writers Peter Y. Hong and John Spano contributed to this report. An unexpected result of Israel's wall: more Arabs in Jerusalem. Times staffers present daily updates from the Phil Spector murder trial. One woman's stamp act Airman testifies deputy shot him despite explanations Spector's lawyers lose bid to use Clarkson's own words Copyright 2007 Los Angeles Times FSBO (For Sale By Owner) Boodle.com for Grocery Coupons Recycler for Free Classifieds
