our next road trip? Evenflo Car Seat Carriers Recalled Prepare Financially for a Disaster Deli Fresh Pet Food: Not Affected by Recall 2007 Wildland Fire Outlook Associated Press - June 4, 2007 7:04 AM ET LOS ANGELES (AP) - The judge in Phil Spector's Los Angeles murder trial is expected to rule today on whether to allow the defense to introduce gunshot victim Lana Clarkson's writings. Judge Larry Paul Fidler said last week that he would likely let defense lawyers use the manuscript in which Clarkson reportedly writes about having visions of a dead actress who killed herself with a gun. A defense attorney says the writings found on Clarkson's computer also include discussions of her fascination with guns, depression over her failing acting career and struggles with alcohol and drugs. The actress died of a gunshot fired inside her mouth in the foyer of Spector's mansion in February 2003. Spector's defense contends Clarkson killed herself. Copyright 2007 The Associated Press. All rights reserved. This material may not be published, broadcast, rewritten or redistributed. All content &copy; Copyright 2002 - 2007 WorldNow and KESQ. All Rights Reserved. For more information on this site, please read our
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/8-6&fd=R&url=http://www.chron.com/disp/story.mpl/ent/4858708.html&cid=1116938747&ei=h4BkRteEHIL0rQO9rMChBg Comforts jokes with real recordings, but laughs not there | Chron.com - Houston Chronicle " width="11" height="11" border="0"> Legal & Public Notices Legal & Public Notices Legal & Public Notices Travel News & Features Legal & Public Notices June 4, 2007, 10:08AM jokes with real recordings, but laughs not there Copyright 2007 Houston Chronicle If you're familiar with Wallace & Gromit, you're familiar with two of the best characters in stop-motion animation. The antics of a cheese-loving British inventor and his faithful dog are warm and funny without being too fuzzy-wuzzy. The same people who created those Oscar-winning characters  along with such family-friendly films as (7 p.m. June 4, CBS/Channel 11). But this time Nick Park and Aardman Animations Ltd. are working without a net. Specifically, they have no script. Instead, they take real audio recordings of ordinary Americans (many in the first episode, June 4, were apparently taken in doctors' waiting rooms) and put their words in the mouths of stop-motion animals. Sometimes it works, as when a lovebird describes in lengthy detail all the doctors she routinely sees. But more often, it doesn't  no matter how funny the animated characters are to look at. The humor just isn't there. True confession: We laughed out loud at the crude opening scene that uses the audio recording of two men at a wine tasting and puts their words in the mouths of two dogs who are sniffing another dog's rear. But here's the point: The laughs are too few and far between to merit a half-hour's viewing. Next time, a script would be nice. Games offer another type of sequel for summer movie fans to go, Tony's future grows dimmer Houston girl wins C-SPAN's 'StudentCam' video contest MyNetworkTV learns what doesn't work, tries new shows Kisses and crude jokes highlight MTV awards jokes with real recordings, but laughs not there Our guide to best entertainment this week Wallace & Gromit return to video Wallace & Gromit: The Curse of the Were-Rabbit To heck with the beach; summer TV is hotter than ever Film review: Animation festival offers visually pleasing shorts 'Were-Rabbit' stop-motion gets 'Flushed' The Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy Buy Photos & Page Prints 2005-Present Historic Page Prints 1901-2004 Copyright Notice & Privacy Policy
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/5-1&fd=R&url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/blogs/sfgate/detail%3Fblogid%3D24%26entry_id%3D17232&cid=1116884258&ei=h4BkRteEHIL0rQO9rMChBg Tim Goodman. The Bastard Machine : "Sopranos" Ep. 20: "A glorified crew." Tim Goodman. The Bastard Machine "Sopranos" Ep. 20: "A glorified crew." I think the point to make upfront here is that, in these last two deconstructions of "The Sopranos," we might not even need to go that deep. Everyone will have theories - though I believe the notion of "theories" is coming to an end - and people will have elements to the franchise series they'll want to go on and on about. I may just be getting in the way. That said, at this point, one paragraph in, I can't promise that it will be short. See you on the train, Bobby. The last episode, however, was truly sweet. And also bittersweet. The most impressive part of this rush to the end is that nearly every episode has been taut, informative and fanstastic. In this penultimate episode (which David Chase co-wrote), you can see the veil of surprise, of artistic feints, red herrings, theory-bating and any other cool narrative device totally vanish. It's as if things snuck up on us. Time is not just running out, it's almost all gone. Action needed to step forth and be counted. And so, true to form historically, the second to last episode had more than it's fair share of Big Moments. By the way, I'll say this once and once only - if you haven't seen this episode, turn away now. Sil whacked a guy (don't listen to offers, is the moral of that killing); Sil was later killed (or at least we think so) as was Bobby Bacala. Tony is on the run, holed up in a safe (unsafe?) house with Bacala's Big Ass Gun and Paulie Walnuts and the rest of the least threatening crew you could ever imagine. Strange times. These have been tense episodes of late and Sunday's may have ratcheted things up to unbearable. Give the directors (and the writers) credit for moving things along at a crisp clip, with everything believable and compelling (even if you knew what was coming - the mark of suberb cinematography and storytelling). The Bacala hit at the hobby shop was tipped by the ringing phone in his left-behind jacket, but even when you saw the two guys walk in, the editing of the train and the guys walking down the aisles and Bacala staring dreamily at his "Blue Comet" train coach - it was priceless. Really well done. And credit Bacala for standing tall as long as he could. He took a lot of led. The Sil hit was perfect because there was a routine to it. A simplicity. Get in the car, get out. Cut off. Do what you can to survive. It seems about as simple and true to life as imaginable. The question here is, were you sad about either one? Strangely enough, I wasn't. Not one bit. I think that's part of the point. So here we are, one episode from the end (did you notice that HBO didn't even play coy with the preview - just kept it short and simple, not to give enough away; that said, knowing Phil has surfaced before Tony is dead is a very bad sign for Phil). Almost without thinking about it, a lot of heated theories about where this series is going are now moot, pointless or just out the window. Forgotten even. I still think there will be a lot of unanswered questions in the finale (and we may yet see Tony die) but this unraveling seems about as simple as you could dream it. Two families have a falling out. New York moves on Jersey. The end. Or at least close to it. There are still ramifications. But the basic motivation for closure seems to be a personality clash and a dispute. Very true-to-life as motivation. Very mob-like. Now, we're still open to interpretations, ideas about what's next (does Tony go or stay, is there a backlash in his family-on-the-lam, etc.) Something could still happen with the Feds. A.J. and Carmela are both still in play. Someone from within his own crew could turn. Tony could even slip away (after offing Phil?) to an unknown life. We may never know a lot of things. But why not talk about them? More after the jump: Phil-isms: "Anthony Soprano has no respect for this thing..." "Plain and simple, we decapitate and we do business with whatever's left." (Brilliant!) "I took his fat f-ing hand in friendship." "Guys don't get their finger pricked. There's no sword or gun on the table." "Either it has meaning, or it doesn't." "Five f-ing families and we've got this pygmy thing over in Jersey." And so, off to war. The PBS "Frontline" Iraq doc was timely, no? So, peer pressure works on psychiatrists as well? Clearly Melfi was pushed into some come-to-Jesus realization by Eliot and his constant pushing of the new research about sociopaths and therapy, as discussed in last week's episode as well. I loved the editing of the words as Melfi read in bed at night, believing that seven years of work with Tony was one long professional dupe, that she had herself been sucked into trying to save him, perhaps, or because she was intrigued by him. " The criminal's sentimentality reveals itself in compassion for babies and pets." There's the A.J. and ducks thing. " The criminal uses insight to justify heinous acts ." Yep, that sounds like Tone. And, on therapy: " For criminals it becomes one more criminal operation Credit Tony, at least, for calling Melfi's sudden reversal "immoral" and nailing her (and therapy in general) to the wall on accountability. Tony was reading (and tearing out) Departures magazine. Nice. Good to see Artie Bucco again, even temporarily. I guess his story is that the restaurant business goes on, and rifts with his wife get patched. There certainly seemed to be more there earlier - a lot more - but you can file that as one of a number of storylines that will never see a proper conclusion. Another tip of the hat to simplicity and mere luck (or being unlucky). The normally professional, can't-miss hit men from Italy get the wrong guy. Once that happened, did it not send a chill up your spine? Like, uh-oh. Phil just dodged one and this is all going sideways. I loved how distraction (the guy in the porn store), faulty delegation and the whimsy of bad timing and bad luck - a lot like life - play into the eventual destruction of much of Tony's crew. Mies was right. God is definitely in the details. Uncle Junior's money is out. Unless they re-dig up the backyard, it looks like state care from here on out. Sil: "Paulie wants it known he takes full responsibility. But he didn't do anything." Perfect! Don't ever change, Paulie. Tony was remarkably calm when he was telling his family. He's focused. Professional. And finally threw A.J. around to wake him up (the point was, hell, if you're not going to move on Miss Lovely and instead choose to mope, I may have to throw you into the closet to wake you up. Pack a bag. No resort wear or sandals, please.) One episode left. Tony's holed up, back to the wall, fully automatic machine gun in hand. Knowing that much will be left unresolved, there's this: How does he go out? How does it end? June 04 2007 at 12:43 PM The beginning of the end. Soon...no more guessing. Posted By: hickcity | June 04 2007 at 12:54 PM I barely breathed during the episode. Possibly dumb question - who did Sil whack? Tim, I did feel bad for Bobby. I know he was not blameless, but out of all the crew, he was the one who seemed to revel the least in the brutality and excess of the life. He would have been happy to have been a civilian. Posted By: smckenna752 | June 04 2007 at 12:56 PM Tony with the machine gun behind the door reminds me of Scarface: "Say hello to my little friend". It would be fitting for Tony to be left standing last and alone, going out in a hail of gunfire. Outstanding episode. Posted By: sdv30 | June 04 2007 at 01:00 PM Very suspicious behavior by Paulie, Parisi and Sil, in that order. Suspicious that Phil and his main guys spared Paulie with a less than adequate explanation ("management only"), and suspicious that Paulie sped off somewhere (to tell Phil to go into hiding?) after seeing the hit men. Then Paulie unable to reach Sil all night because his wife had "food poisoning"? Was Sil working with Phil or the Feds? The order to kill that Burt guy didn't come from Tony, so who did it come from? Maybe Burt was an informant and Sil was afraid his own association with the FBI would be revealed, or maybe Sil was working with Phil who had him killed for appearances or to eliminate anyone whose allegiance could later be questioned. Also, we don't know for sure that the call on Bacala's cell phone was a warning call from Sil. Maybe Sil never made that call for a very specific reason. Or maybe he took his time about it. How do we know? Wondering if Janice will bolt and leave the kids to be raised by Carm. Another chance for her to parent? Loved the episode! Great build to the finale! Posted By: tall_chick | June 04 2007 at 01:02 PM I love how Phil puts all the blame on his brother's death on New Jersey when it was New York who ordered and paid for it. Posted By: TimSPC | June 04 2007 at 01:02 PM Nice decon, Tim. I loved the reference to "Raging Bull", when the theme music is playing in the background and Tony and Sil start shadow boxing. A great sly reference to the fact that these are aging dons, about to hit the canvas. It would be funny, if it wasn't so sad. Will Tony sleep with the fishes in the finale? Will he survive? Either way, I don't think it matters. We now see how he has paid for his lifestyle, for his choices. He is a man at the end, whether he "survives" or not. He's lost. Posted By: alibaba3 | June 04 2007 at 01:03 PM Bobby was careless - especially after having stepped up to take care of the matter for Tony. In many ways the beef Phil has with Tony's "crew" is real - loyalties have outweighed skill and ability for too long. Bobby was just such a point in fact. No one, including Paulie, seemed to really pay attention to detail in carrying out Tony's orders on the Phil hit. Its definitely personal for Phil, and now that his goomah has be offed he may try to strike even deeper at the heart before he completes the decapitation. And that may ultimately be his undoing... I was not convinced of this episode's depiction of a "final" meeting with Tony and Dr. Melfi. If that scenne does end up being the final meeting then I must defer from Tim. If anything was rushed in order to usher forward the inevitable conflict that was not a complete moment. Posted By: leake | June 04 2007 at 01:06 PM Flatbush Bikini Waxing. What a butch meeting place (I will NOT say hidey-hole!) for Phil's homophobic crew. Posted By: maenad | June 04 2007 at 01:09 PM The last scene of Tony alone on a bare mattress holding an assault rifle is perfect. I guess that wasn't his childhood room in his mom's old house but it looked like it could be. Posted By: blinky | June 04 2007 at 01:10 PM You know what they say: You live by the model train, you die by the model train... Posted By: UncleBoo | June 04 2007 at 01:16 PM I don't even want to speculate, but I wouldn't bet against Tony even if he's pretty alone now. I watched the last four episodes back to back last night with some friends who hadn't seen eps 17, 18 & 19 (I'd seen them twice) and I'm still pretty gobsmacked today. What an intense ride this has been. It was really clear how well the foundation was laid for all that was to come. ~Some people have commented that Melfi's quiting as Tony's therapist was out of character or forced but I think it was very believable. Her perception of her relationship with him is paralleling our own. Melfi's was seduced by Tony as we all were, felt uncomfortable about it at times but she was also in denial. She is now seeing him for who he really is too --and I think she feels "dirty" for her role in it. She just saw the light, SHE got it. And I thought it was great how he called her on it. He is a smart man, he did learn some things in therapy, but did it ultimately change who he was? We'll see. But Melfi won't. Posted By: suzyq2 | June 04 2007 at 01:16 PM Something dawned on me this morning. As Sil and Patsy were cleaning out the back room at the Bing (right before they got hit), Sil asked Patsy to grab a bunch of paperwork (believe he said "receipts"). Unless I missed it, I think this was still in the backseat of the car in a briefcase as Patsy ran off (where did he get to btw?). Could this be the final info that implicates the NJ "glorified crew"? I need to watch this episode again, as there were so many small things I missed (like the Sil Dante cutout in the safehouse). Posted By: mudcrutch2000 | June 04 2007 at 01:17 PM Don't you think it's possible that Janice will snap out of her "mourning", suspect Tony whacked Bobbie (he had just badmouthed him to Janice a scene or two earlier), and take him out, in revenge for supposedly killing Bobbie and leaving her high and dry, concerning Uncle Junior? Posted By: leahbrooks | June 04 2007 at 01:23 PM Countless fine details in this episode: * Cutting from the violence of Sil's whacking of Bert to Phil stirring his espresso in a very mannered, cultured way. Great filmmaking. * The music in The Bing -- "When The Music's Over". Music is your only friend, until the end. * At home, AJ plopping down in front of the Frontline doc, looking just like Tony doing the same in front of the History Channel. The narration of the show even sounded the same. My speculation: Phil may regret leaving Paulie off the hit list. Paulie may be a loose cannon, but he's Tony's loose cannon. His story has to get wrapped up in some significant way, and I can't help but feel that it has to be central to Tony's. Not that I've forgotten about AJ, mind you... God, I'm gonna miss this show. Posted By: jim_at_sfgate | June 04 2007 at 01:23 PM Is there any realistic possibility that Bert Gervasi tried to flip Silvio over to NY, but somehow didn't first do the same with his own blood cousin (Carlo)? I'd think Carlo would be the first guy he'd go to, even for nothing else but to test the waters before he went to the #2 guy in the family. Carlo certainly has no love for Tony, especially after Tony essentially said he valued Vito (a fanook!) more than him. Carlo killed Fat Dom, hand-to-hand, for less. At the end of the episode, it was Carlo who needed a reason to use his cell phone from the secret new safe house. Maybe the pizza will get delivered by Butchie .... Posted By: blackjack33 | June 04 2007 at 01:26 PM A couple of nice references: Carm, in the elevator going to AJ's hospital room, to Tony - "Only one more week of this..." "The End" by the Doors playing in the Bing. Posted By: jtl46 | June 04 2007 at 01:30 PM At our house we have had the increasingly strong suspicion that Paulie has been playing both sides for a while now. Left off Phil's list...odd that the Italians would screw up something this important...unaccounted for time during this "crisis" ... I read above about Sil maybe being with Phil or the Feds...maybe...but I don't trust Paulie. And there he is in Tony's safe house at the 11th hour... Posted By: trillo_in_marin | June 04 2007 at 01:33 PM As for next week: I always assumed Tony would go while fetching the Star Ledger in his bathrobe from the foot of his driveway. But Burt Gervasi got that treatment, thanks to Sil. Now we've got the Iraq metaphor: Phil Leotardo, who really just wants to avenge his family's name, hopes to quickly decapitate Jersey, figuring he can work with whatever remains. Finishing the George Bush parallel, AJ watches Frontline's segment on Iraqi insurgents. So Tony's now the insurgent, fighting for his life against Phil (which trumps depression any day, at least in the short term). He'll probably prevail, but be left with very little: Paulie Walnuts, an empty house, an empty pool (no place for the ducks to land), and with only the realization that he can fill his father's shoes after all (plenty of shoes in episode 20)--but that's all he can expect. Posted By: sophieluv | June 04 2007 at 01:33 PM SuzyQ2 is dead-on in her take of the Melfi-Tony confrontation. Great scene, totally believable. Jim_at_SF_Gate: funny, I had the same feeling about Paulie, as well. He seems perfectly within his element as the boys are going to the mattresses . . . Posted By: spearchamp | June 04 2007 at 01:36 PM Long time reader... first time poster... Maybe someone more insightful than I can make this parallel make sense... But did anyone else read into Tony concerning himself with Agent Harris' anti-terrorism work, only to be snapped into reality by the information that NY was planning on hitting his crew (information that upset him enough that he actually discarded the sandwich he was eating... did you ever expect to see Tony Soprano upset enough to stop in the middle of eating something and throw it out?). Meanwhile, A.J. is holed up in his mansion watching Frontline Iraq specials and reading internet terrorism news when Tony has to snap him into the reality of the current situation to let go of his depression and be a man for the family. I feel like there's something to that. I never expected the terrorism storyline to really flesh out in the end, and I'm really thinking now that David Chase was just trying to draw a parallel here. There was even a brief shot of Tony staring at the terrorist news site on A.J.'s computer and shaking his head in disbelief. Posted By: wcm99 | June 04 2007 at 01:44 PM I agree with you and Jim_ about Paulie. I've been watching the whole shebang from the beginning (thank you netflix!) and just watched the episode in which Paulie approaches Carmine (Big Carmine?) at the wedding. Carmine has no idea who he is. Cut to Paulie facing himself (and what a face!) in the (pishadu) mirror. He realized then that he was with Tony, for good. Posted By: maenad | June 04 2007 at 01:45 PM I don't think Paulie is in cahoots with NY - he went down that road once and nearly got burned. What I DO believe is that Phil and Co. are shrewd enough to realize that if they achieve their goal of knocking out T, Sil, and Bobby, that would leave Paulie as the likely puppet leader - certainly no match for Phil. It was interesting, though, to watch how the two Families prepared for "war". Tony's decision was to basically "outsource" the work, and Bobby (for all the confidence that Tony showed in him) basically started a "sh*t rolls downhill" approach until it essentially wound up in Patsy Parisi's hands (Tony, meanwhile, went to get new tires for his wife's car). Phil, on the other hand, laid out his strategy concisely, and Butchie made it very clear as to who was to do what to whom and when. Great illustration of Phil's up-front declaration of the relative merits of the 2 Families. Posted By: spearchamp | June 04 2007 at 01:52 PM maenad, I guess we were thinking about the same point regarding Paulie . . . Posted By: spearchamp | June 04 2007 at 01:56 PM The dread in this episode was almost too much to take. Seeing Bert in his driveway, getting the morning paper, was unsettling; having Sil walk up was terrifying, until they exchanged greetings, and then seeing Sil sneak up behind Bert with the piano wire was like getting hit over the head. And that was just the opening scene! And at the end, watching Tony in bed with his big-ass gun, we got a view of him from outside through the window, and my blood ran cold. Posted By: dsgonzale6 | June 04 2007 at 01:58 PM My theory: Paulie as Judas hands Tony over to Phil for some big showdown moment. The show has been ephasizing Paulie Walnuts going "crackers" in recent episodes, which would make him just stupid enough to take as big a risk as betraying Tony. Paulie is also a classic narcissist and so in order to elevate himself within one family or another, he could very well deliver Tony unto Phil. Like Phil, Paulie is obsessed with old-school ways and so there could be a natural alliance struck there. It also seems suspicious to me that the hit overlooked Paulie in favor of Bacala, who was not nearly as senior. Something smells fishy there... Posted By: Carmela_lite | June 04 2007 at 02:03 PM great minds think alike! Posted By: maenad | June 04 2007 at 02:03 PM A few weeks ago, Tony viewed Paulie as something between annoying and expendable. Now, compared to the cast of characters left in the safe house, Paulie looks like a Jeopardy champion. I can see room for some irony here, as Tony's prior oncern over whether Paulie has ever "really been tested" plays out as follows: Tony sings to the FBI while Paulie dies standing his ground. Of course, in granting Paulie the "best of the worst" status in the remaining safe house crew, I'm assuming that Carlo's cell phone call from the safe house wasn't really driven by hunger for pizza .... Posted By: blackjack33 | June 04 2007 at 02:08 PM I think Sil is going to live. The doctor's "don't think he'll regain consciousness" but that's far from dead. An interesting point is that Tony's crew doesn't need to be threatening, they just need to pull some triggers. Says a lot about who criminals are. They aren't these grandiose men of action, they are fat slackers who couldn't do anything else with their lives. I love Phil blaming New Jersey on a lack of tradition. Classic argument from old guys, blaming some trivial artifact from the good ole days for why things aren't as good as they used to be. "You know what the problem is these days? These kids got no respect..." Posted By: rhys1882 | June 04 2007 at 02:09 PM Brutal episode. Truley a trainwreck of an episode. I particularly liked the hit on the wrong people. In that 5 minutes, we had gratuitous violence, vut right to hardcore porn. So many balances in this episode, and I couldnt breathe when Tony was telling AJ to get the f*** out of the house. I was expecting NY to roll up any second. Posted By: imageburn13 | June 04 2007 at 02:10 PM In the end, Butchie gets it. Paulie gets it. Phil gets it. And yes, Tony has to get it. Hey ... Seriously, Carmela has to pay some sort of price in the end for her superficial, mob money-fueled, double-standard existence. You can't have it both ways, hon, and you've escaped for seven years. You don't even know Ade's dead! Think of all the wives in this show who ultimately paid the price in some way for being ``married to the mob'' -- Rosalie Aprile, Angie Bompansero, Ginny Sacremoni, Vito's wife, Christopher's wife, now Sil's wife and even Janice, who I almost felt sorry for when the family came to console her in the old Sack estate. All survived, but their flimsy mob-financed lifestyles were ruined. Has to happen to Carmela ... has to. Can't wait to see her fate, maybe more so than Tony's, which is pretty well cast. Agreed it was good to see Artie again. Even the minor characters in this show will be missed. Speaking of which, where's Benny? Did I miss a whack somewhere? Posted By: tarastew | June 04 2007 at 02:10 PM , great point re: Melfi's & the audience's feelings on Tony. Posted By: TimSPC | June 04 2007 at 02:11 PM First time comment. Love your work, Tim. Was going to say the same stuff about Paulie but the previous posts said it all. There's one wild card here: the Feds. With an informant (and if I'm right, a wire) in Phil's presence ordering the hit on Bacala, Sil and Tony, and with Bobby and Sil then hit, the Feds now have enough evidence to arrest the whole NY gang on conspiracy charges. On top of that, they owe Tony something but owe Phil nothing. Final result could be that Tony, who wants nothing more than finding a way out of this life, in charge of not only Jersey, but Phil's family also. Talk about irony. I really don't believe a word of this, by the way, but what the hell, it's speculation. Posted By: cerritoguy | June 04 2007 at 02:16 PM Does anyone know, is the last episode 1.5 hrs (ala Wire)? Posted By: sdv30 | June 04 2007 at 02:17 PM The Doors' "When The Music's Over" as stripper music in the first Bing floor scene. Nice choice, especially since that wouldn't have been strip-club music even when it was new. Posted By: Tek Jansen | June 04 2007 at 02:17 PM To protect our readers from malicious comments SFGate asks that you login or register to post a comment. Sign On to post your comment. Remember me on this computer Forgot password or screen name? By submitting this comment you agree to the Not a member yet? Register now. Live outside the US? By submitting this comment you agree to the Everything We Know We Learned From Television. So don't lie to me like I'm Montel Williams. is the Television Critic for the San Francisco Chronicle. In addition to criticism, he covers the industry and writes trend and analysis pieces, mostly about failure. Listen to Tim Goodman's on all things television. Some helpful A's for your Q's. Podcast with Stephen Colbert: KFOG Morning Show Podcasts Death March With Cocktails Listen to Tim's podcasts Death March With Cocktails The CW (UPN & WB) "Sopranos" Ep. 20: "A glorified crew." "Deadwood" fans, your heads are about to explode. TV Talk Machine: Worst. Podcast. Ever. I've got your blog right here, pal. TV Show Face-Off! The season is over! All hail the victor(s)! Other TV Critics I Like (Partial List.) Television: Drug of the Nation TV Shows On DVD Sing It Like You Mean It God Is In the Details The Office Episode Guide Subscribe to The Bastard Machine: What is My Feeds? &copy; 2007 Hearst Communications Inc.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/8-2&fd=R&url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/06/03/AR2007060301355.html%3Fhpid%3Dsec-artsliving&cid=1116938747&ei=h4BkRteEHIL0rQO9rMChBg CBS's 'Creature Comforts': A Brit-Witty Feat of Clay - washingtonpost.com Find Bars & Clubs View a Sample and Sign Up House Majority Leader Tom DeLay Indicted CBS's 'Creature Comforts': A Brit-Witty Feat of Clay Washington Post Staff Writer Monday, June 4, 2007; Page C01 It's been a grim summer television season so far. Steven Spielberg's reality show on Fox about wannabe movie directors is a flop and a bore. Fox's "So You Think You Can Dance" and NBC's upcoming "America's Got Talent" are bad "American Idol" rip-offs. And did anyone catch that train wreck last week on CBS about pretend pirates searching for hidden treasure? Aaaargh indeed. The stop-action animals of "Creature Comforts" share their Aardman Animations pedigree with Wallace and Gromit. Tune in to the shows coming to airwaves this summer with our premiere calendar. Save & Share Article But take heart, channel surfers. The first bright spot of the hot months arrives tonight, and we've got a bunch of animated animals to thank for it. Created by the British company responsible for the popular "Wallace & Gromit" movies, "Creature Comforts," an animated half-hour comedy debuting tonight at 8 on CBS, is clever and often hilarious. The premise? The show's producers record the voices of "real people" throughout the country as they talk about everyday topics such as doctor visits, keeping secrets and the attraction between the sexes. These voices are bestowed upon various animal characters who all bear that familiar Claymationed "Wallace & Gromit" look. "Creature Comforts" opens tonight on a slightly crude note, but it's hard not to laugh. The voices of two men, apparently recorded at a wine tasting, are given to a pair of dogs sniffing a third dog where dogs generally sniff each other. "It smells pretty ripe," the dog says earnestly. "I'm getting medium to dark notes. Also, kind of a dry fruit character to it." Some of the must-see "Creature" characters include: two lovebirds sitting in their cage, where the wife lists her various ailments while her put-upon husband sits by; two porcupines discussing their fear of needles; a hippopotamus who hates being weighed by nurses, all of whom are skinny; and a pair of frisky bunnies discussing their love lives. The humor in the show derives from how perfectly the animal characters (dogs seem to be a specialty) and their expressions match the voices that are provided. In general, the jokes don't stray from PG-rated territory, save for a randy toucan who claims he's a "bisexual" -- "I like to ," he explains with a cackle. One 5-year-old viewer, who clearly didn't get any of the humor of the show, was still howling at the various animals that popped up onscreen. The biggest laugh for him was a water-fearing polar bear wearing floaties on his legs. (30 minutes) premieres tonight at 8 on WUSA (Channel 9). The Trouble With McFriends Paula Abdul Audio Tape Leaked to Media Seacrest a Laughmaker in `Knocked Up' Spoleto Festival to Honor Menotti Related Topics & Web Content Top 35 Most Viewed Comments that include profanity or personal attacks or other inappropriate comments or material will be removed from the site. Additionally, entries that are unsigned or contain "signatures" by someone other than the actual author will be removed. Finally, we will take steps to block users who violate any of our posting standards, terms of use or privacy policies or any other policies governing this site. Please review the governing commentaries and discussions. You are fully responsible for the content that you post. &copy; 2007 The Washington Post Company Refinance Rates As Low As 2.9% - FREE QUOTES! $300,000 Mortgage for $965&frasl;mo! Refinance & Save $1,000's! Be Prepared. Fight Identity Theft! Equifax.com. $425,000 Loan for only $1,417&frasl;mo