http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/17-4&fd=R&url=http://www.earthtimes.org/articles/show/69232.html&cid=1116966251&ei=h4BkRteEHIL0rQO9rMChBg Chicago divorce case draws interest Chicago divorce case draws interest Mon, 04 Jun 2007 17:58:01GMT Create your own RSS CHICAGO, June 4 A Cook County (Ill.) Circuit judge will decide whether the multimillionaire head of a Chicago energy firm must give his ex-wife half of his fortune. Michael Polsky, 57, who heads Invenergy LLC, has been ordered to give Maya Polsky, 55, some $176 million in a divorce case viewed as remarkable and historic, the Chicago Tribune reported. Lawyers for Michael Polsky argue that he alone was responsible for building the couple's wealth after they emigrated from Russia in the 1970s. His wife, who stayed at home, contends she was her husband's trusted confidant and should be considered a full partner in his success. Her lawyers argue she should get more than half the wealth because Michael Polsky's future earning power is greater than hers. Boyd promised to rule this week on whether his division of the property last October would stand. In addition to valuable artwork, furniture and jewelry, the couple had five homes. Copyright 2007 by UPI Email this article (Click Here) Share this article on &raquo; - Billboard raises eyebrows in Chicago | 07 May 2007 - British divorcees' assets threatened | 10 May 2007 - Suspect charged in Sen. Braun case | 21 May 2007 - R. Kelly still to face judge | 27 May 2007 - Rock, paper, scissors on hand in Las Vegas | 13 May 2007 U.S. Rep. Jefferson indicted for bribery Hezbollah reported rebuilding in Lebanon NATO: Putin's remarks not welcome Putin: Missile shield could trigger war England bans palace protests The views expressed in the articles are not necessarily those of earthtimes.org and we accept no responsibility for the views or opinions expressed in the articles either direct or indirect. , All Rights Reserved.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/5-4&fd=R&url=http://www.boston.com/ae/tv/blog/2007/06/the_penfreaking.html&cid=1116884258&ei=h4BkRteEHIL0rQO9rMChBg The Pen-Freaking-Ultimate Episode - Viewer Discrection - The Boston Globe Before I make a few little points about last night's tense, mind-blowing, excellent episode of "The Sopranos," I have... is the Globe's TV critic. is the Globe's pop culture reporter and critic. Ask a question or share an idea with The Boston Globe's TV writers. RSS feed for this blog Add to My Yahoo For Boston Globe television reviews, visit &laquo; But the Geeks are Only So Powerful Ex-wives and ex-cars &raquo; Monday, June 4, 2007 Before I make a few little points about last night's tense, mind-blowing, excellent episode of "The Sopranos," I have to warn readers that there are in this entry, and they are you will definitely want to avoid until after you've watched. My whole body was on edge during the show, which built quickly to full-on gang warfare after years of moving in that direction. "Ready for the rapture?" was the FBI agent's comment to Tony, and to us. As soon as I realized it was Phil and his evil-looking goons against the likes of Tony, Sil, Bobby, and Paulie, I knew the New Jersey guys were doomed. I loved the little bit of "Raging Bull" between Tony and Sil while they strategized in the restaurant; another nice passing homage to Martin Scorsese. Tony is now without his best ally, the comatose Silvio, who'd earlier in the episode made a malapropism about his wife being "terminally" ill. There was a brief moment during the shooting when Silvio was crawling in the car that reminded me of the way Adriana crawled before he shot her (an important reminder, since I tend to romanticize Sil's loyalty). And Bobby was nixed in a great shooting scene that built slowly and eerily at the train store, the center of Bobby's innocence. I loved it that kids were screaming; they were delivering the sounds Bobby, the eternal child, couldn't. The handling of Melfi's rejection of Tony was powerfully done, I thought. Her built-up contempt for him -- and for her own naivete -- was painful to watch. Elliot is a complete creep, and unethical, too, as he told Melfi's social circle about her client. Is he jealous of Melfi's encounters with a famous criminal? Dude's got issues. The entire series was framed by Tony's therapy sessions, and so I'm glad to see David Chase (who cowrote last night's episode) giving the therapy theme some importance in the end. I wouldn't be surprised to see Melfi back in some way next week, even as part of a coda. Without Melfi, Sil, Bobby, and Christopher, and with his family safely elsewhere, Tony is left alone in a bed with a gun in some mysterious safe house. I don't believe he will off himself, although the camerawork teased us with that possibility as he climbed onto the bed. I'm more of the mind right now that Paulie, so two-faced, will kill Tony, or at least try to, in hopes he'll survive with Phil. Or will Tony give up his life to save Carmela, or A.J., in one big act of self-sacrifice that will prove Elliot (and now Melfi) wrong? I'm not holding my breath... I can't wait for next week; and I'm dreading it, too. All good things must pass, I guess. Did you see the episode? Talk about it on "The Sopranos" message board. Posted by Matthew Gilbert at E-mail to a friend The New York Times Company
