till-in-development Battlestar prequel ; while a script has been sitting on the shelf over at the cabler, no decision about its future has been made. Jace is an LA-based television development and acquisitions junior exec who watches way too much television for his own good and would love a TiVo for every room in the house. (He?s halfway there.) His blog, Televisionary, can be found at Add your voice to the conversation and share your opinions. Please keep your comments relevant to this post. Inappropriate or purely promotional comments may be removed. Also please note that at this time, each person will only be able to comment once on a particular post, so make yours count. We're working on some things in the future to reward our most thoughtful and active commenters. You are not signed in. You need to be to add a comment. &#171; Previous Story | | Next Story &#187; The Latest on Film.com All the Latest in Movies All the Latest in DVD All the Latest in TV Latest Celebrity News and Gossip A chef assembles a hilariously dysfunctional and wildly libidinous staff, and things really start cooking, both in the kitchen and in the bedroom! Kitchen Confidential: Dinner Date Kitchen Confidential: French Fight Kitchen Confidential: Rabbit Test The Best of the Writer Rants Occasionally our people get riled up. Here&#039;s what happens when they do. Advice for Lindsay Lohan Cage as Capone? C&#039;mon. No Wall Street 2! Opening Credits Have Got to Go The Disaster of Shrek 4 Is Guy Ritchie Dead? Surely You Jest James Bond Shame on You Paramount Web in Your Eye Visit other RealNetworks sites: &#169; 2006 RealNetworks, All Rights Reserved
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/6-4&fd=R&url=http://www.thestar.com/living/article/221126&cid=1116968833&ei=h4BkRteEHIL0rQO9rMChBg TheStar.com - living - In search of the `happily ever after' Full Text Article Archive TheStar.com - living - In search of the `happily ever after' In search of the `happily ever after' Knocked Up explores the sweet wistfulness of wanting to make relationships work Jun 04, 2007 04:30 AM &#34;What makes a happy lifetime partnership after all?&#34; It's a question writer/director Judd Apatow explores through the lives of two couples in his new hit movie, There's the 24-year-old svelte blonde broadcaster who's pregnant after a drunken hook-up with a 23-year-old schlubby slacker and quintessential jerk. And there's her older sister, married with kids to a wealthy music agent. They're not exactly an inspiring role model: &#34;Everybody's all pissed off all the time.&#34; Observes one character, &#34;A marriage is like an unfunny, tense version of The effort to have a happy partnership is not only at the tender heart of this movie, it's also the subject of almost every self-help book that's not about losing weight. That's because much of life is about a yearning for contented coupledom, the strategy to find it, and the struggle to maintain it. And it's why, along with all the raunch in , there's also the sweet wistfulness of wanting to make relationships work. &#34;Think we'll ever be as happy as the Baby Bjorn couple?&#34; asks father-to-be Ben, catching sight of the image on the baby carrier box. Chances are they will. Because whereas most couples begin by mistaking chemistry and passion for authentic intimacy and knowing each other, Ben and Alison are merely sharing an embryo. Not blinded by love, they can coolly and rigorously scrutinize each other as potential partners: &#34;We have seven months until the baby comes ... seven months of getting to know each other.&#34; &#34;Falling in love, people idealize each other,&#34; says Toronto psychoanalyst and couples therapist Keith Haartman. &#34;It's a wonderful state to be in but can never sustain itself. They always have to confront each other's foibles and limitations.&#34; Ben and Alison do this with brio from the beginning. Generally in dating, &#34;you don't even look at each other through the spousal lens,&#34; says John Van Epp, author of How To Avoid Marrying A Jerk . The Ohio-based relationship counsellor believes &#34;has some embedded wisdom.&#34; He says it's wise that Alison &#34;doesn't move in or agree to marry Ben: forcing him to be independent is more revealing.&#34; He adds, &#34;It's wonderful to have a depiction of somebody getting better over the course of a relationship.&#34; People can change, he says, but &#34;you don't want to change them. You want to see if it's self-maintaining. Three to six months is a good rule of thumb.&#34; (Just as in a new relationship, &#34;Around three months you start to see things not evident in the first two months.&#34;) Ben and Alison are doing just what Guy Grenier prescribes in his book, The 10 Conversations You Must Have Before You Get Married &#34;Co-ordinating needs, wants, desires, likes and dislikes,&#34; he says, &#34;is five times more difficult than rocket science. Taking it for granted, thinking it just happens, is naÃ¯ve and dangerous.&#34; But figuring it out, says the London, Ont., psychologist and marital therapist, &#34;can be a lot of fun.&#34; &#34;The more similarities, the easier and the better, and the greater the likelihood you're not going to be in conflict,&#34; he explains. While one big difference in important areas such as family, money, sex, kids and religion won't be fatal, Grenier warns, &#34;10 will be.&#34; Healthy relationships, he says, deal well with three critically important issues: attachment, autonomy and equality: &#34;People need to feel the relationship is equally costly and equally benefiting.&#34; The three things couples fight about most? &#34;Chores, money, sex.&#34; But, suggests Haartman, &#34;In the vast majority of instances, what people are arguing about is not what they're arguing about.&#34; Very often, he says, couples repeat traumas of childhood and with previous partners in hopes of finding some resolution. &#34;Each partner may demand of the other that they right the wrongs of the past.&#34; Sometimes, however, it all comes down to determination to make it work, for any number of reasons. &#34;Would she have stuck with it if she hadn't been pregnant?&#34; Van Epp wonders about the movie. Apatow's response to the over-arching relationship question? &#34;There's something honourable about ... not breaking up for the sake of the baby,&#34; he told the . &#34;I see people get divorced and there is a part of me that thinks, `I wonder how hard they tried?'&#34; Horse, heiress and a hurdle Charities worthy of donations Great home delivery subscription deals here! More in the news A tale of two schools Killed sister in self-defence, accused murderer says Grieving families demand answers McGuinty promises no tax hikes Trump not expected at Black trial: Lawyers Harper talks green ahead of G8 WWF rips U.S., Canada environment records Aviation security suspect, Air India probe told Four guards guilty of beating prisoner MOST POPULAR ON THESTAR.COM Grieving families demand answers Man out of 19-year coma Horoscopes for Monday, June 4 Paris Hilton goes to jail Highrise fall kills toddler Interest sags in nude retreats Man out of 19-year coma Grieving families demand answers Napoleon's love letter found in laundry room What they got: June 2 Careers at the Star Pages of the Past Star Store & Photo Sales &copy; Copyright Toronto Star 1996-2007
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/7-0&fd=R&url=http://seattlepi.nwsource.com/local/6420AP_WA_Starbucks_McCartney.html&cid=1116768102&ei=h4BkRteEHIL0rQO9rMChBg Starbucks' music label debuts with new Paul McCartney CD Skip ads and navigation Last updated June 4, 2007 1:40 p.m. PT Starbucks' music label debuts with new Paul McCartney CD By ELIZABETH M. GILLESPIE SEATTLE -- Caffeine junkies who go to Starbucks for their daily fix will get a nonstop dose of Paul McCartney's "Memory Almost Full" on Tuesday as the coffee company's new record label releases its first CD. Starbucks Corp. estimates that some 6 million people will be among the first to hear the new album as they line up for their lattes in more than 10,000 stores in 29 countries, where it will be playing on continuous loop throughout the day. It's a tactic most retailers would not likely attempt "probably for no other reason than not wanting to drive their workers insane," quipped Mike McGuire, an analyst for Gartner Inc. Still, McGuire said Starbucks has proved to be adept at selling music and thinks it's smart for the company to tap into its vast customer base. "Let's face it. The energy has kind of gone out of the CD store launch," McGuire said, "so you've got to go where (consumers) are, which is typically buying coffee at a Starbucks." Ken Lombard, president of Starbucks' entertainment division, said he's not worried about customers or baristas succumbing to McCartney overload. "To the contrary, we think everybody's going to be really excited," he said. Starbucks co-founded its Hear Music label with Concord Music Group in March. McCartney was in the final stages of recording and mastering his latest set of songs when he signed a one-album deal with Hear Music, becoming the label's first artist. "Once we heard the album ... we just knew this was a phenomenal record," Lombard said. "It is the most personal and revealing album that Paul has created in his solo career. ... It's such a reflection of his life and his career, I mean, the ups and downs and the recognition of really what a remarkable journey it has been. So it was really for us the perfect fit." Lombard said he hasn't set any sales targets for "Memory Almost Full" but that he'd be "ecstatic" if it ends up rivaling "Genius Loves Company," an album of Ray Charles duets that Starbucks and Concord co-released in 2004. It won eight Grammy awards the following year and has sold more than 5.5 million copies worldwide. McCartney remains Hear Music's only artist, but Lombard said the label remains on track with previously announced plans to sign two more artists this year and eight next year. Executives remain hopeful that McCartney will sign on for future albums. "The relationship is going very well between us, and it is our hope that Paul is feeling the same way," Lombard said. "When the time is right, we'll talk about what the next steps are going to be beyond this, but right now our focus is doing everything we can to ensure that 'Memory Almost Full' is an extraordinary success." A spokesman for McCartney declined to comment. In addition to playing and selling the album in its stores, Starbucks got XM Satellite Radio Holdings Inc. to play McCartney music exclusively on one of its channels Tuesday, putting "Memory Almost Full" in heavy rotation. Hear Music has also hired crews in London, New York, Berlin, Los Angeles, Philadelphia, Atlanta, Seattle, Hong Kong, Tokyo and Miami to film footage of McCartney fans wishing him happy birthday for a video tribute that will be broadcast on Internet social-networking sites, including Google Inc.'s YouTube, Yahoo Inc.'s Yahoo360 and Microsoft Corp.'s Windows Live Spaces, on the artist's 65th birthday June 18. Most labels lean heavily on artist appearances for CD releases, but Lombard said Monday it was not yet clear exactly what McCartney would be doing the day of the release. "Paul likes to work in a way that he comes in and provides a great surprise to his fans and to music consumers, and that's an approach we're all on board with," Lombard said. Hear Music hasn't completely abandoned more traditional marketing methods, but is relying a lot less on advance radio play and music reviews ahead of "Memory Almost Full's" release. The album will be sold at most Starbucks stores worldwide, in all major music retailers, and on Apple Inc.'s iTunes online music store, making it the first of McCartney's 21 solo albums to be released digitally. Add AP Local headlines to Jogging Elvises and more Keep it simple with a high-tech kitchen He's bad with money; don't bank on him Man in bulletproof vest scares Everett school Starbucks' music label debuts with new Paul McCartney CD Justices address legal standard for proving violations in credit reporting cases 4-year-old boy dies after being pulled from Clear Lake Fort Lewis Stryker brigade soldier killed in Iraq Machinists at Spokane Triumph plant reach deal Airbus plans to produce 13 A350 aircraft per month by 2016 Man shot to death in Bremerton apartment Body found in burned out car near Elma Memorial service tomorrow at Fort Lewis for four soldiers Former fire commander sentenced to 2 years prison for arsons Fire in Sequoia National Forest burns 1,000 acres Feds sued over removal of grizzlies from threatened list Wyoming still will wait to control wolves Comic Relief donates $155,000 to Tahoe animal shelter Gates Foundation donates $105 million to UW for health center After a half-century in the skies, pilot made mistake No. 1 Limited interest in City Council races State doubles funding to protect public lands Ceremony ushers in change for Reserve, Fort Lawton P-I staff on Seattle politics Challenger takes on Godden Primary vote will decide 51 percent of state GOP's National Convention delegates Giuliani not New York's favorite son Group claims captured troops were killed Rep. Jefferson indicted in bribery probe Bush opens Europe trip on jarring note Guantanamo judge dismisses terror case G