http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/7-1&fd=R&url=http://www.boston.com/news/globe/living/articles/2007/06/04/mccartneys_memory_proves_just_a_bit_spotty&cid=1116768102&ei=h4BkRteEHIL0rQO9rMChBg McCartney's 'Memory' proves just a bit spotty - The Boston Globe McCartney's 'Memory' proves just a bit spotty Anyone mystified by the news that Paul McCartney has abandoned his longtime record company, EMI, and hitched his wagon to Starbucks' Hear Music label hasn't fully considered the marketing potential of this venture. McCartney's 'Memory' proves just a bit spotty By Joan Anderman, Globe Staff | Anyone mystified by the news that Paul McCartney has abandoned his longtime record company, EMI, and hitched his wagon to Hear Music label hasn't fully considered the marketing potential of this venture. For starters, tomorrow McCartney's new album will play all day in every Starbucks store in the world. That's some mighty cross-promotion, and it will almost certainly produce huge first-week sales. But it won't make "Memory Almost Full" a great album. This collection is filled with half-baked ideas and shallow reminiscences, a pair of dated rockers, and one meditation on mortality that manages to be maudlin and bubble-headed at the same time. It smacks of Wings at its goofiest. Of course even Wings had Paul McCartney in the band, and the man can write a charming melody. High points on the album include "Mr. Bellamy," a quirky, chamber-pop portrait that meanders through several movements, and the final minute of "Feet in the Clouds," where McCartney slices and dices his voice into lovely, machine-treated layers. "Dance Tonight," the opening song and lead single, is barely a song, more of a smiling aural snapshot of strummed mandolin and stamping foot. But in its simple grace the tune feels far more substantial than much of the deceptively orchestrated fluff that follows. For his 21st solo album McCartney gave the boot to Nigel Godrich -- the longtime Radiohead producer who coaxed such remarkable depth from the artist on 2005's "Chaos and Creation in the Backyard" -- and reunited with David Kahne , who produced Macca's 2001 disc, "Driving Rain" (as well as recordings by a slew of other artists from the Bangles to the Strokes). By the sound of it, Kahne was content to play with arrangements and knobs. He plumps and ornaments peppy ditties like "See Your Sunshine" and a dead-end blues called "That Was Me" with enough instrumental cheer to generate an effervescent vibe, if not quality songcraft. But there was no smart editing, no big-picture conversation, no quality control. McCartney needed someone to tell him that his exhortation on "Vintage Clothes" (Don't live in the past!) doesn't jibe with the "Ever Present Past" he celebrates so jauntily (and with so many '80s-style synths) a few songs earlier. Or that "Gratitude" is a bad song. Or that "Nod Your Head," a harsh and creepy amalgam of "Why Don't We Do It in the Road?" and "Live and Let Die," was an ill-advised way to close this lightweight album. &copy; Copyright 2007 Globe Newspaper Company. All Globe stories since 2003 are now FREE E-mail to a friend Living / Arts RSS feed The New York Times Company
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/5-6&fd=R&url=http://www.philly.com/inquirer/magazine/7825952.html&cid=1116884258&ei=h4BkRteEHIL0rQO9rMChBg 'Sopranos' chat: Who needs a therapist? | Inquirer | 06/04/2007 About the Philadelphia Inquirer , sports venues and more. See a photo you want? Photos of the day Beach and Bay Homes Active Adult 55+ Housing Monday, Jun 4, 2007 Posted on Mon, Jun. 04, 2007 reprint or license this 'Sopranos' chat: Who needs a therapist? Maybe the show's heart-stricken fans. It's a crime this show has to die next week, say the Inquirer's Jonathan Storm and Karen Heller. Splitsville: Dr. Jennifer Melfi (Lorraine Bracco) and Tony Soprano (James Gandolfini). Not that she really helped. As `Sopranos' End Nears, So Does Tony's States Work to Lure Film, TV Production What was your favorite Sopranos' moment? How do you think the series will end? Well, that was certainly something. Unbelievable. I'm still reeling. What did you think? It is very rare for a TV show to have my heart racing while watching it, but last night's show had to be one of the best in recent memory of any TV series. It's hard to say what was more brutal, Melfi dropping Tony as a client after seven years or Phil trying to take out the top of Tony's crew. I think the episode and, it seems, the entire show, is stirring indictment of psychotherapy. The catty therapists citing limited data and Melfi's instant dropping of Tony in a totally unprofessional way. As Tony said, it really was immoral. Yes, the odious Eliot Kupferberg (played by the equally odious Peter Bogdanovich) violating therapeutic ethics is just as bad as Phil. What did you think of the botched job by the Italians? They killed the father of Phil's housekeeper or goomar, depending on which website you read. (HBO says it's the housekeeper but a lot of bloggers think she was his mistress.) Think that was an accident set up by the increasingly mysterious Paulie? Is it just me, or do you think that Paulie is the rat? Phil specifically chose not to kill him. He botched the Phil hit. Phil was tipped of by someone, that's why he skipped. I didn't see that at all, until you mentioned it. It's possible, but I still find it hard to believe. I though it strange that Phil ordered to take out Tony, Sil and Bobby, accomplishing the latter, pretty much incapacitating Sil and now searching for Tony but Paulie, a made man, was left out. He's been absent a lot and acting a bit wifty. He could definitely be working for Phil or the feds. Paulie is playing both sides of the fence. Phil say no to his hit and Paulie mess up the hit on Phil. Plus Tony wanted to whacky Paulie and had a change of heart. Sicilian by marriage: Tony shoulda taken Paulie out when he had the chance. He knew what to do and 'wussed-out'. He'll live (or more likely, die) to regret it. Phil said Paulie was not "in management." So he has a logical excuse, and it's possible Phil sent that lookalike guy into harm's way. I am a trusting soul. Two points 1. re therapy: Elliott's behavior at the dinner party was obscene, but also crystallized Melfi's ambivalence throughout the whole series. She doesn't truly believe, I don't think in whether her treatment of Tony is really having any effect, and Elliot's abuse of confidentiality, plus power over Melfi pushes her over the edge; second, the hits on Bobby and Silvio both reprise AJ's quoting of Livia to the effect that we all die in our own arms. Everyone else has left Tony; all he has is the gun. Tony has been left by Melfi and now has to leave Carmela. How soft is Bobby, not having his haunches up after meeting with Sil and Tony to discuss the possible ramifications of their actions against Phil, and then go about his business of building his toy train empire like it's just another day. No wonder he was such an easy hit. I thought Bobby's death scene was just so beautifully filmed. "The Blue Comet" (title of the show and name of a now defunct NYC-Atlantic City Express) was such a nice metaphor. Things were once so elegant. And the beautiful stationing of the litte plastic figures on the train set. "Oh, No, Mr. Bill," one of them seemed to be saying, holding her had to her face. And the incredible speeding trains, with Bobby crashing into the entire beautiful creation as little children screamed. That scene was amazing, worthy of Scorsese (honored again with a homage to ). Yes, it should of been called the Red Bullet. Bobby was always childlike, and the most endearing of the crew. What's T going to do when he's just left Paulie -- maybe -- and a bunch of drivers? The hit on Silvio was equally well-made and perhaps more difficult to film. And Mr. Chase and crew, in addition to indicting virtually every segment of modern American society also had a little insult for us in the audience. are the clowns who came out of the Bing and gasped and groaned as Silvio was popped and then the motorcylclist was knocked off his bike and crushed. By the way... did anyone else notice the priest in the crowd at 'The Bing'? Leave it to to make us laugh in the middle of such a sad and gruesome scene. Yes, there was so much collateral damage last night -- the cyclist (I agree that scene was amazing, the whole episode was), the bystanders at the train store, the strippers and clients at the Bada Bing, Tony's family. Didn't you love AJ's selfishness mirroring that of of his father? His response to Uncle Bobby's death was "I was already having so much trouble maintaining." Tony watched WWII movies. AJ is watching Iraq videos. Both suffer from depression and self-absorption. That whole amazing packed episode was only 49 minutes, with credits. There does not appear to be any way out for "T"... unless the feds can "rescue" him and he goes into witness protection. I think there are lots of ways out, but then you have to imagine what "out" will be. His family (both of them) is riven. Rebuilding will be almost impossible even if he does survive. Is there a 9/11 analogy here? Tony has no future. His family (both of them) are decimated by death - of the body and soul. He has no future and the final episode will cement that. There are two overriding ways the series can end: With a literal bang, for Tony or Phil, or quietly. David Chase, who co-wrote last night's episode, trends toward violence in the penultimate episode of each season. A colleague says he visited a Jersey bakery which claims to be the site of the last scene, suggesting a somber or poetic ending rather than an operatic one. Tony is already alone. But, then, he's been that way for some time. To me, that's the whole arc of the series. That even a man surrounded by two families is ultimately alone and in Tony's case, his multitude of sins. Tony could still turn to the feds. Don't forget- he threw away his italian sub after meeting with the fed at Sattrili's! He's ready to give up the life. I mean, after last week, who's left to protect??? What are the possibilities of a final duel between Tony and Phil? The writers have had Tony watch a bunch of western movies over the years? Well, I never watch previews for series, but in this case I feel it's part of my job, and Phil was certainly a presence in the preview, which was called "The Final Episode Ever," subtitled: "No More Hiding." Who's hiding from whom? Can you say "everybody"? I believe that Christopher playing the soundtrack from 'The Departed' was prophetic. All principle characters were dead at the end of that movie. Chase is looking to close the book on this entire series and the possibility of any stupid 'reunion' shows. Everyone's hiding. Money, or lack thereof, was also a big theme. With Bobby dead and Sil out of the picture, Paulie acting wifty, Tony hiding, Carmela worried about money, Janice asking for funds for Uncle Junior's rest home, it's a huge worry. Money is the engine, and the engine's stalled. I loved Janice talking about Uncle Junior's accountant. "With the larynx box, June thinks he's from Outer Space." I love Janice. She's so horribly wonderful. And I miss Junior and Johnny Sac, who was such a wonderful adversary though Phil is angrier. I miss them all. Nobody's talked about Carmela ... the scene at Artie's where she's putting the best face on Meadow's career decision, and Tony going to the mattresses ... strips away all of the years of denial she's been living in. Could she lie anymore to Charmaine? She's as bad as Tony with Artie. Sure, she's pleased about Meadow with Patrick Parisi, dating the son of an underling, and thinking about criminal law when, we all know, she would be representing the criminals, not prosecuting them. It was as artificial as her nails. Life may be harder for Carmela than for Tony at the end of all this. Absolutely. She's a junkie for the lifestyle. And here's my theory: Meadow, smart and competent, rises to become head of the family. It should be interesting regardless of the turnout this Sunday. If you think about it, there have been so many "Twin Peaks" moments the last couple of years. The dream sequence after T was shot was never again addressed, nor was the epiphany during the sunrise in Vegas. What do you think of the possibility of having all of our "dearly departeds" returning in the final episode as Tony lays dying? How about Chase doing a "prequel" to the show? Meadow and AJ, do we hear echoes of Michael and Fredo Corleone? Chase doesn't like to tie up thinks neatly. That's why he's a genius. I don't want a prequel with Gandolfini and Falco in bad wigs. We already had Sil for that. Also, let me just offer the three worst words in cinematic history: . We can only pray that someone gives Chase a lot of money to do an entirely different project. Any chance Tony lives through the next episode? For me, who lives and dies and so forth is certainly interesting, but I am dying inside that everybody will be gone after Sunday. The whole thing is dying, and it has been so fine for so long. I think I may be even sadder about this than I was about the end of Maybe Tony can pick up Lorelai as his goomar. Or Rory. Jon, you would be in heaven. He could marry Lorelia and have Rory on the side, and I would be in heaven. I think who lives and dies is important, though almost everyone has died, but it's more important where the series leaves us emotionally. I mean, Livia's death wasn't planned -- the fantastic Nancy Marchand died -- but you mourn her still. And the show has increasingly left Tony alone. He's isolated socially and emotionally. Uncle Junior was such an excellent foil. I still haven't forgiven Chase and Co. for making him daft. He always had the funniest lines in the show, and was a worthy emotional and political adversary. I love/loved Uncle Junior and Dominic Chianese who played him. The glasses were almost as good as Steve Van Zandt's hair. Are we all going to die, too? It's such a common thing with good television. Shows get canceled and millions of fans go crazy (people have sent, like, 14 tons of peanuts to CBS for some obscure reason to try to resurrect ) and then new shows come along. In the case of some, however, the loss really is palpable. has been as good as TV gets. Yes, next week I plan to make Carmela's baked ziti (found the recipe on the web) and uncork an excellent Barola to mourn. Not sure anything will replace this. I may have to start watching all over again with the first season. Jonathan, Your last comment says it all. Do you think Tony's changed at all over the course of the series? I do. I think, unfortunately for him, he has seen more clearly who he is and what he does. And that has made him even angrier and more violent. It's one thing merely to be a beast. It's quite another to be human and do inhuman things. I have always thought of Tony as King Lear, but now I'm seeing him more as Richard III. Interesting. Because the point of the therapists' dinner last night was that sociopaths -- and Tony is definitely that -- just perfect their bad behavior through talk therapy. They perfect their lies and the stories they tell themselves. I don't think he is a sociopath. He follows a lot of rules. And I do not take the conversation or the research at face value. I think it was just a convenient way for the psychotherapists to remain detached and above it all, as they always do. I think the instant dumping of Tony and the little jealous stuff from Elliott and the complete disregard for their rules says much more about the terribleness of the therapists than anything else. If what our colleague says about the bakery turns out to be true, perhaps it's a pun on 's "leave the gun, take the cannoli." This episode ended with Tony alone with his AR-10, a battle rifle that was gift from Bobby. Perhaps next week he takes the cannoli and puts down the gun after Phil is gone. Although Tony is in no position to take on the wrath of the NY crew. Phil started it, so I think Tony would have some support having eliminated a guy who defied the rules. The rules again. I guess I really don't care to speculate too much on how it's going to end. I would rather be surprised. They can't end with both Tony and Phil in hiding. That would seem corwardly and a fight that ends in a standoff, a riff on powerlessness that I don't think the show would explore in a final episode. One of them has to go down. I think it would have more power if it was Tony because he's the guy we've all come to know, and become strangely attached to, despite what a beast he is. I'm sure whatever happens, I'll be sitting there aghast and depressed. But we shouldn't forget. Right after, comes the premiere of , the new one from David Milch ( Hill Street Blues, NYPD Blue, Deadwoo d). He's no slouch, so maybe we'll all have something new to chat about. I'm there. Until -- sob - next week when we have our wake. Yup. See you, and all our fellow chatmates, who have such interesting ideas, then. Updated 4:00 PM EDT MOST VIEWED IN THIS SECTION 'Sopranos' chat: Who needs a therapist? Ask Amy | Values 