http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/16-4&fd=R&url=http://www.courierpostonline.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article%3FAID%3D/20070604/LIVING/706040337/1004&cid=1116948888&ei=h4BkRteEHIL0rQO9rMChBg 'Sleeping Beauty' revival a success CourierPostOnline - South Jersey's Web Site Give a gift subscription Submit a news tip Spot News Kids Korner Letters to the editor Weddings, Engagements & Anniversaries 'Sleeping Beauty' revival a success Three stars of four The cast: Princess Aurora: Arantxa Ochoa Prince Desire: Zachary Hench Lilac Fairy: Valerie Amiss Carabosse: Riolama Lorenzo White Cat: Abigail Mentzer Puss 'n Boots: Matthew Neenan Princess Florine: Amy Aldridge The Bluebird: Francis Veyette Music by Peter Ilyich Tchaikovsky. Choreography by Marius Petipa. Additional choreography and staging by Janek Schergen. Set and costume designer Peter Cazalet. Lighting designer John Hoey. Presented by the Pennsylvania Ballet at the Academy of Music, Broad and Locust streets, Philadelphia through Saturday. Tickets are $10 to $122. Call (215) 893-1999 or visit Monday, June 4, 2007 "The Sleeping Beauty" is the ultimate test for a dance company. The Pennsylvania Ballet passes the test in a revival of Tchaikovsky's fairy-tale ballet at the Academy of Music. "The Sleeping Beauty" stretches the company to its limits -- some of the court dances look underpopulated -- but the dancing is strong and secure. Peter Cazalet's traditional sets provide a handsome frame for the dancers. The court scenes look properly grand and stately, although the designer's muted costumes lack vivid color. For the forest scene, Cazalet conjures up a menacing tangle of trees that provides a dramatic backdrop for the confrontation between Prince Desire and the evil fairy before his kiss awakens Princess Aurora. This "Sleeping Beauty" marks a farewell for Valerie Amiss after 15 years with the company. As the Lilac Fairy, Amiss displays the grace and charm that have personified her dancing in a wide variety of roles. Arantxa Ochoa (Aurora) and Zachary Hench (Desire) added some star power to Friday evening's performance. The audience repeatedly broke into applause during their scenes together. Ochoa danced with care at her first appearance in the opening act. She struck form in the grand pas de deux in the wedding scene. Supported commandingly by Hench, Ochoa danced with a blend of elegance and quiet fire. Ochoa's lithe grace was matched by Hench's power. Hench proved to be a strong partner. He lifted Ochoa without effort and held her confidently. The final act celebrates the power of dance in a sequence of magical divertissements. Heidi Cruz-Austin (Diamond), Ian Hussey (Gold) and James Ihde (Silver) expertly performed the Precious Jewels pas de trois. Then Puss 'n Boots (Matthew Neenan) pursued the White Cat (Abigail Mentzer) in a playful duet. Adding to the pleasure was the spirited dancing of Maximilien Baud, Jonathan Stiles and Andre Vytoptov as the Three Ivans. Francis Veyette and Amy Aldridge left their imprint on the taxing duet for The Bluebird and Princess Florine. Veyette's physical power contrasted nicely with Aldridge's elegant dancing. Throughout the evening, the Pennsylvania Ballet's corps adds to the pleasure of this "Sleeping Beauty." The women contributed some relaxed but precise dancing in the second act. Beatrice Jona Affron and the Orchestra of the Pennsylvania Ballet provide solid support for the dancers. Summoning spirited playing from her musicians, the conductor generates excitement in the pit. Reach Robert Baxter at (856) 486-2436 or send a letter to the editor This article does not have any comments associated with it Find a used car to buy Find a used Car: Find a New Car Send feedback about CourierPostOnline.com Copyright ©2007 Courier-Post. All rights reserved. Users of this site agree to the Privacy Policy/Your California Privacy Rights (Terms updated March 2007) .Build 0: 718 ms (Misc) .Build 9: 0 ms (Content)
