http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/8-5&fd=R&url=http://www.jsonline.com/story/index.aspx%3Fid%3D613181&cid=1116938747&ei=h4BkRteEHIL0rQO9rMChBg JS Online: Out of the mouths of big-toothed 'Creatures' Music & Night Life Journal Sentinel Newspaper Service Center Subscribe to the Journal Sentinel Manage Your Subscription Account Make Us Your Home Page Setting Your Home Page About the Journal Sentinel Questions about accessing stories? See our Frequently Asked Questions page. Buy a link here Out of the mouths of big-toothed 'Creatures' Posted: June 1, 2007 With conventional sitcoms fumbling and floundering, it's refreshing - and too rare - for network TV to try a different kind of funny. "Creature Comforts," where have you been? Actually, if you get BBC America on satellite or digital cable, you know where this animated treat has been: on British TV, where the voices of typical blokes and birds in the street have issued from the mouths of whimsical animals for years. And if you've seen "Wallace & Gromit in The Curse of the Were-Rabbit" or "Chicken Run," you're familiar with the work of Nick Park's Aardman Animations, which produces both the British and American versions of "Creature Comforts." The distinctive Aardman style of stop-motion animation uses claylike figures in the shapes of all manner of creatures, from floppy-eared rabbits to garrulous goldfish. Apart from chattiness, what they all have in common is toothiness: Even the chickens sport sizable choppers.
